text: X-linked myopathy with excessive autophagy (XMEA) is a type of myopathy and a specific form of X-linked recessive disease, which has a material basis in some form of X-linked recessive inheritance. It is characterized by symptoms such as muscle weakness and progressive weakness. The condition is defined by the onset of progressive muscle weakness and atrophy mainly affecting the proximal muscles in males between 5 and 10 years old, and it results from a mutation in the VMA21 gene located on chromosome Xq28.

Adenylosuccinase lyase deficiency is a type of amino acid metabolic disorder characterized by microcephaly, aggressive behavior, cerebellar hypoplasia, and seizures. It has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the ADSL gene, resulting in adenylosuccinate lyase deficiency.

Arc syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a syndrome, which particularly has its material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by congenital joint contractures, renal tubular dysfunction, cholestasis, severe failure to thrive, ichthyosis, and a defect in platelet alpha-granule biogenesis. This condition arises from homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the VPS33B gene or homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the VIPAR gene, both located on chromosome 14q24.3. Arc syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms: Arthrogryposis, Renal Dysfunction, and Cholestasis (ARC) syndrome, and Arthrogryposis-renal dysfunction-cholestasis.

Armfield syndrome is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability characterized by intellectual disability, short stature, seizures, and small hands and feet, and in some cases, cleft palate or cataracts/glaucoma. The condition has its material basis in variation in the chromosomal region Xq28. It is also known by several exact synonyms including Armfield X-linked mental retardation syndrome, MRXSA, X-linked intellectual disability, Armfield type, mental retardation syndrome, X-linked, Armfield type, and syndromic X-linked mental retardation Armfield type.

Neuroacanthocytosis is a type of neurodegenerative disease. It is defined as a neurodegenerative disease characterized by misshapen, spiny red blood cells (acanthocytosis) and neurological abnormalities, especially movement disorders.

Choreaacanthocytosis, also known exactly as Levine-Critchley syndrome or choreo-acanthocytosis, is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a form of neuroacanthocytosis. It is characterized by a condition that inherently has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, Choreaacanthocytosis is defined as a neuroacanthocytosis characterized by progressive neurodegeneration and red cell acanthocytosis, typically beginning in the third to fifth decade of life. The condition is caused by homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the VPS13A gene, which is responsible for encoding chorein, located on chromosome 9q21.

Midface dysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia, which is defined as an osteochondrodysplasia characterized by features such as hypertelorism, a wide nose, vertical midline cleft, and encephalocele.

Mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency nuclear type 1 (MC5DN1) is a specific type of mitochondrial complex V ATP synthase deficiency and a disease that is fundamentally based on a structural variant. This condition is defined by a deficiency in mitochondrial complex V (ATP synthase) that has its material basis in a mutation in the ATPAF2 gene located on chromosome 17p11.

N syndrome is a type of syndrome that is characterized by intellectual disability, deafness, ocular abnormalities, T-cell leukemia, cryptorchidism, hypospadias, and spasticity. It is also exactly synonymous with NSX.

Polycystic liver disease, which is a type of autosomal dominant and liver disease, is defined by the presence of multiple cysts in the liver. This disease also has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance patterns. It is exactly synonymous with congenital cystic liver disease, congenital hepatic cyst, and fibrocystic liver disease.

Pheochromocytoma is a type of endocrine organ benign neoplasm and is a condition that at least has the symptom of some high blood pressure. It is defined as an endocrine organ benign neoplasm that arises within the adrenal medulla, which releases epinephrines and norepinephrines hormones, causing either episodic or persistent high blood pressure. Additionally, pheochromocytoma has an exact synonym, phaeochromocytoma.

Spastic ataxia 1 is a type of spastic ataxia and an autosomal dominant disease that is characterized by early-onset cerebellar ataxia, spasticity, pyramidal syndrome, and peripheral neuropathy. It has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance, specifically through the heterozygous mutation in the VAMP1 gene located on chromosome 12p13.

Paraganglioma is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of pheochromocytoma that has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a pheochromocytoma that arises in extraadrenal sympathetic ganglia. Furthermore, paraganglioma is exactly synonymous with chemodectoma and glomus body tumor.

Rapadilino syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease and syndrome that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It also exhibits symptoms such as diarrhea. The syndrome is defined as being characterized by a radial ray defect, patellae hypoplasia or underdevelopment, cleft palate, diarrhea, dislocated joints, limb malformations, a long nose, and normal intelligence. This is due to a homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the DNA helicase gene RECQL4 located on chromosome 8q24.

Schneckenbecken dysplasia is a type of osteochondrodysplasia characterized by hypoplastic iliac bones, hypoplastic vertebral bodies, short ribs, and broad long bones. It is prenatally lethal and has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutations in the SLC35D1 gene located on chromosome 1p31.

Non syndromic X-linked intellectual disability is a type of X-linked monogenic disease, as well as a type of non syndromic intellectual disability. It is also categorized as a type of condition that, at the very least, has a material basis in some X-linked inheritance. This condition is defined as a non-syndromic intellectual disability characterized by an X-linked inheritance pattern. Additionally, it has an exact synonym: non-specific X-linked mental retardation.

Joubert syndrome is a type of ciliopathy and a type of brain disease, specifically a condition where at least one disease is located in the brain. It is defined as a ciliopathy characterized by congenital malformation of the brainstem and agenesis or hypoplasia of the cerebellar vermis, leading to an abnormal respiratory pattern, nystagmus, hypotonia, ataxia, and a delay in achieving motor milestones. Additionally, Joubert syndrome has an exact synonym: JBTS.

Meckel syndrome, which is a type of ciliopathy, is characterized by renal cystic dysplasia, occipital encephalocele, polydactyly (post-axial), hepatic developmental defects, and pulmonary hypoplasia. It is also exactly synonymous with Meckel-Gruber syndrome.

Hydrolethalus syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease that fundamentally has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is precisely defined as a syndrome characterized by multiple fetal developmental defects including polydactyly and central nervous system malformations, which results from a single amino acid mutation of D211G of the HYLS1 gene, playing a central role in cilia formation. Additionally, Hydrolethalus syndrome is exactly synonymous with Salonen-Herva-Norio syndrome.

Ogden syndrome is a type of syndrome, more specifically, a type of X-linked monogenic disease, which is a kind of condition that fundamentally has a material basis in some form of X-linked inheritance. It is characterized by postnatal growth failure, severely delayed psychomotor development, variable dysmorphic features, and hypotonia, and it has a material basis in either X-linked recessive or X-linked dominant mutation in the NAA10 gene on chromosome Xq28. Furthermore, Ogden syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including N-alpha-acetyltransferase, N-terminal acetyltransferase deficiency, OGDNS, and X-linked Malformation and Infantile Lethality Syndrome.

Zollinger Ellison Syndrome is a type of syndrome that is defined as a condition characterized by the development of one or more tumors (gastrinoma) in the pancreas, duodenum, or both. These tumors secrete excessive levels of gastrin, a hormone that stimulates the production of acid by the stomach.

Secondary progressive multiple sclerosis (SPMS) is a type of multiple sclerosis characterized by a worsening of disability, rather than by relapses followed by recovery. This condition progressively worsens until a steady progression of disability replaces the cycles of attacks. It is exactly synonymous with SPMS and Secondary-progressive MS. Additionally, secondary progressive multiple sclerosis has a narrower match with MESH:D020528.

Primary Progressive Multiple Sclerosis (PPMS), also known as Primary-progressive MS, is a type of Multiple Sclerosis characterized by steady worsening of neurologic functioning without any distinct relapses or periods of remission. Although the rate of progression may vary over time, with occasional plateaus or temporary improvements, the progression is continuous. Furthermore, it has a narrower match with MESH:D020528.

Progressive relapsing multiple sclerosis (PRMS), also known as Progressive-relapsing MS, is a type of multiple sclerosis. It is defined as a form of multiple sclerosis characterized by steadily worsening symptoms and attacks during periods of remission, with disease progression from the onset. Moreover, it has a narrower match with the MESH identifier D020528.

Iridogoniodysgenesis syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of iris disease, which is based on some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is characterized by hypoplastic iris stroma due to abnormalities in the differentiation of the anterior segment structures, along with increased values of intraocular pressure, stemming from autosomal dominant inheritance of mutations in the PITX2 gene. This condition is precisely identified as IGDS, IRID 1, IRID 2, iridogoniodysgenesis type 1, and iridogoniodysgenesis type 2.

Juvenile polyposis syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of gastrointestinal system disease. It is characterized by a predisposition to hamartomatous benign polyps in the gastrointestinal tract, specifically in the stomach, small intestine, colon, and rectum. This condition has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and typically starts during young adult onset.

Proximal symphalangism is a type of autosomal dominant disease, syndrome, and bone disease. It is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and its location in some bone element. This syndrome is defined by ankylosis of the proximal interphalangeal joints, carpal and tarsal bone fusion, and conductive deafness. Furthermore, proximal symphalangism has an exact synonym, Cushing's symphalangism.

Tarsal carpal coalition syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of dysostosis, which at least has a material basis in some autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a dysostosis characterized by the fusion of the carpals, tarsals, and phalanges, the shortening of the first metacarpals causing brachydactyly, and humeroradial fusion.

Fibular hypoplasia and complex brachydactyly, which is also known by its exact synonyms Du Pan syndrome and acromesomelic dysplasia-2B, is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, acromesomelic dysplasia, and a condition that fundamentally arises due to autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, this type of disorder notably affects the bones. It is specifically defined as an acromesomelic dysplasia characterized by a severe reduction or absence of the fibula and complex brachydactyly.

Persistent Mullerian Duct Syndrome is a type of reproductive system disease and a type of pseudohermaphroditism, which is located in the reproductive system. It is defined as a pseudohermaphroditism that is characterized by the persistence of Mullerian duct derivatives (i.e., uterus, cervix, fallopian tubes, and upper two-thirds of the vagina) in a phenotypically and karyotypically male. Its exact synonym is Persistent Muellerian Duct Syndrome.

Multiple cutaneous and mucosal venous malformations (VMCM), also known exactly as cutaneomucosal venous malformation and mucocutaneous venous malformations, is a type of disease that is classified under autosomal dominant diseases, skin diseases, and vein diseases. This condition is characterized by multiple bluish cutaneous or mucosal venous lesions, with its material basis being a heterozygous mutation in the TEK gene on chromosome 9p21. It relates to autosomal dominant inheritance and has its location in zones of skin and veins.

Short QT syndrome is a type of heart conduction disease, which is also characterized as a condition that manifests at least some arrhythmia as a symptom. It is defined as a heart conduction disease that features heart arrhythmia, specifically identified by a short QT interval on an EKG (less than 300 ms) that remains relatively stable across different heart rates, alongside tall and peaked T waves, and is associated with a structurally normal heart.

Multiple synostoses syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and dysostosis. It is characterized by a condition that has at least a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This syndrome is defined as a dysostosis that is characterized by multiple joint fusions, usually commencing in the hands, conductive deafness, and distinctive facial features, including a broad, tubular-shaped nose and a thin upper vermilion.

Cone dystrophy is a type of retinal disease characterized by the loss of cone cells, which are the photoreceptors responsible for both central and color vision. It has an exact synonym, retinal cone dystrophy, and an exact match MESH:D000077765.

Achalasia microcephaly syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease that is characterized by specific features and symptoms. It has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is associated with symptoms such as vomiting. The disease features intellectual disability, microcephaly, and achalasia, which involves abnormal enlargement of the esophagus, impaired peristalsis, cardiospasm, recurrent vomiting, and respiratory infections. This syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms, ACHALASIA-MICROCEPHALY SYNDROME and Achalasia microcephaly.

Peroxisomal acyl coa oxidase deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also a type of peroxisomal disease. It is defined as a peroxisomal disease characterized by hypotonia and seizures in the neonatal period and neurological regression in early infancy, having a material basis in homozygous mutation in the ACOX1 gene on chromosome 17q25.1. This condition is exactly synonymous with Peroxisomal acyl-coenzyme A oxidase and has exact matches in various medical databases: GARD:4543, NCI:C170437, ORDO:2971, SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01:238069004, and UMLS_CUI:C1849678.

Cerebral creatine deficiency syndrome is a type of amino acid metabolic disorder and is also categorized under diseases that are located in the cerebrum. It is defined as an amino acid metabolic disorder that is characterized by mental retardation, severe speech delay, behavioral abnormalities, and seizures. This condition has a material basis in a mutation in the creatine transporter gene on chromosome Xq28.

Guanidinoacetate methyltransferase deficiency is a type of cerebral creatine deficiency syndrome, which is defined as a cerebral creatine deficiency syndrome characterized by severe intellectual disability, seizures, speech problems, and involuntary movements. This condition has its material basis in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the GAMT gene on chromosome 19p13. Furthermore, guanidinoacetate methyltransferase deficiency is exactly synonymous with cerebral creatine deficiency syndrome 2 and is also referred to as GAMT deficiency.

Cerebral creatine deficiency syndrome 1 is a specific type of cerebral creatine deficiency syndrome. It is characterized by mental retardation, severe speech delay, behavioral abnormalities, and seizures. This condition is caused by a mutation in the SLC6A8 gene located on chromosome Xq28. Cerebral creatine deficiency syndrome 1 is also exactly synonymous with CEREBRAL CREATINE DEFICIENCY SYNDROME 1, SLC6A8 deficiency, and creatine transporter deficiency.

Androgenic alopecia is a type of alopecia that is defined as an alopecia characterized by M-shaped hairline recession and thinning of hair at the crown of the head in males. It has the exact synonyms alopecia androgenetica and male pattern baldness, as well as androgenetic alopecia.

Ehlers Danlos syndrome spondylodysplastic type 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also a subtype of Ehlers Danlos syndrome. This condition is characterized by an aged appearance, developmental delay, short stature, craniofacial disproportion, generalized osteopenia, defective wound healing, hypermobile joints, hypotonic muscles, and loose but elastic skin. The material basis for this syndrome is a compound heterozygous mutation in the B3GALT6 gene. It is known by the exact synonyms "EHLERS-DANLOS SYNDROME, PROGEROID TYPE, 2" and "Ehlers-Danlos syndrome progeroid type". Additionally, it has related synonyms such as "XGPT deficiency", "defective biosynthesis of proteodermatan sulfate", and "xylosylprotein 4-beta-galactosyltransferase deficiency". This syndrome is an example of a condition that arises from autosomal recessive inheritance.

The glioblastoma classical subtype is a type of glioblastoma that is defined by being a glioblastoma characterized by abnormally high levels of epidermal growth factor receptor and the absence of p53 mutations.

The glioblastoma proneural subtype is a specific type of glioblastoma. It is defined as a glioblastoma characterized by mutations in IDH1 and p53, along with the amplification of Platelet Derived Growth Factor A.
The glioblastoma mesenchymal subtype, characterized by the most frequent number of mutation of the Neurofibromin 1 gene, is a type of glioblastoma.

The glioblastoma neural subtype is a specific type of glioblastoma. It is defined as a glioblastoma characterized by the expression of several gene types that are also typical of the brain's normal, noncancerous nerve cells, or neurons.

Kahrizi syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease, which has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by mental retardation, cataracts, coloboma, kyphosis, and coarse facial features, with its material basis in a mutation in the SRD5A3 gene. Additionally, Kahrizi syndrome has exact synonyms including KHRZ, intellectual disability, Kahrizi type, and intellectual disability-cataract-coloboma-kyphosis syndrome.
Mucopolysaccharidosis IX is a type of mucopolysaccharidosis characterized by a deficiency in hyaluronidase.

Biotin deficiency is a type of nutritional deficiency disease characterized by a specific set of symptoms. These symptoms include thinning of the hair, often accompanied by a loss of hair color, and a red scaly rash around the eyes, nose, and mouth. Additionally, biotin deficiency is also known by the exact synonym "B7 deficiency."

Congenital adrenal hyperplasia is a type of physical disorder, a steroid inherited metabolic disorder, and it falls under disorders that have their basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth. It is defined as a steroid inherited metabolic disorder characterized by adrenal insufficiency and variable degrees of hyper or hypoandrogeny manifestations, which result from a deficiency in steroidogenic enzymes. Furthermore, congenital adrenal hyperplasia is exactly synonymous with adrenal hyperplasia 1, congenital lipoid adrenal hyperplasia, and lipoid CAH.

Spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia Pakistani type is a specific form of spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia, which is an autosomal recessive disease. This condition has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by characteristics including short stature, short and bowed lower limbs, mild brachydactyly, kyphoscoliosis, abnormal gait, enlarged knee joints, precocious osteoarthropathy, and normal intelligence. Additionally, "spondyloepimetaphyseal dysplasia Pakistani type" is an exact synonym for this condition.

Spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia with congenital joint dislocations is a type of physical disorder, specifically a form of spondyloepiphyseal dysplasia. It falls under the category of diseases that have their basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth, and it affects the skeletal joints. This condition is characterized by short stature of prenatal onset, joint dislocations including the knees, hips, and radial heads, club feet, and limitation of range of motion that can involve all large joints. It is also known by several exact synonyms: CHONDRODYSPLASIA WITH MULTIPLE DISLOCATIONS, CHST3-Related Skeletal Dysplasia, Humero-spinal dysostosis with congenital heart disease, Kozlowski Celermajer Tink syndrome, Omani Type, Spondyloepiphyseal Dysplasia, humero-spinal dysostosis, and humerospinal dysostosis.

Temtamy Preaxial Brachydactyly Syndrome is a type of syndrome that falls under the category of autosomal recessive diseases and is characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by a syndrome marked by features such as brachydactyly, hyperphalangism of digits, facial dysmorphism, dental anomalies, sensorineural hearing loss, delayed motor and mental development, and growth retardation, all attributed to a homozygous mutation in the CHSY1 gene. Moreover, it is exactly synonymous with PREAXIAL BRACHYDACTYLY SYNDROME, TEMTAMY TYPE.

Urofacial syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive disease, syndrome, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by inverted facial expressions in association with a severe and early-onset form of dysfunctional urinary voiding. Moreover, Urofacial syndrome has exact synonyms: Ochoa syndrome and hydronephrosis with peculiar facial expression.

Stargardt disease is a type of age-related macular degeneration characterized by progressive vision loss, usually to the point of legal blindness. It is also exactly synonymous with Stargardt Disease 1.

Transcobalamin II deficiency is a type of vitamin B12 deficiency and is also known as TCN2 deficiency. It is defined as a vitamin B12 deficiency characterized by a lack of vitamin B12 intestinal absorption resulting from a deficiency in the B12 transport protein TCII.

Atrioventricular block is a type of heart conduction disease and is defined as a heart conduction disease characterized by the impairment of the conduction between the atria and ventricles of the heart. It has the exact synonym "AV block" and an exact match with MESH:D054537.

First degree atrioventricular block is a type of atrioventricular block and is defined as an atrioventricular block that is characterized by a prolonged PR interval on an electrocardiogram, caused by delayed conduction from the atria to the ventricles through the atrioventricular node.

Second-degree atrioventricular block is a type of atrioventricular block and has an exact synonym, second-degree heart block. It is defined as an atrioventricular block characterized by progressive prolongation of the PR interval on consecutive beats followed by a blocked P wave on an electrocardiogram, or intermittently non-conducted P waves not preceded by PR changes on an electrocardiogram, caused by a conduction block between the atria and the ventricles through the atrioventricular node.

Third-degree atrioventricular block is a type of atrioventricular block characterized by bradycardia, hypotension, hemodynamic instability, and complete dissociation between P waves and QRS complexes on the electrocardiogram. This occurs when conduction fails to propagate from the atria to the ventricles. It is also known as a complete AV block.

Sinoatrial node disease is equivalent to a condition that intersects diseases located at the sinoatrial node and is a type of both muscular and heart conduction disease. It is defined as a heart conduction disease characterized by dysfunction of the impulse-generating (pacemaker) tissue located in the right atrium of the heart, which generates normal sinus rhythm. Furthermore, Sinoatrial node disease has the exact synonyms "SA node" and "sinuatrial node."

Endocardium disease is the same as a disease that intersects with at least one disease located in the endocardium. It is a type of heart disease. Endocardium disease is defined as a heart disease that is located in the innermost layer of tissue that lines the chambers of the heart.

Tricuspid valve disease, also known as RH, rheumatic disease of the tricuspid valve, tricuspid disease, disease of tricuspid valve, and rheumatic tricuspid valve disease, is a type of heart valve disease. It is equivalent to diseases that are located in the tricuspid valve, which is between the right atrium and right ventricle. This condition is characterized by valvular insufficiency or valvular stenosis, specifically located in the tricuspid valve.

Rheumatic heart disease is a type of heart valve disease and is also a type of condition that always presents with some inflammation as a symptom. It is defined as a heart valve disease characterized by repeated inflammation with fibrinous repair, resulting from an autoimmune reaction to Group A beta-hemolytic streptococci (GAS), leading to valvular damage. The key anatomical alterations in the valve encompass leaflet thickening, commissural fusion, and the shortening and thickening of the tendinous cords. Furthermore, rheumatic heart disease is exactly synonymous with rheumatic carditis.

Artery disease is the same as something that represents the intersection of vascular disease and a condition where at least one disease is located in an artery. Furthermore, artery disease is a type of vascular disease. Moreover, it is defined as a vascular disease that is located in an artery.

Pericardium disease is defined as a cardiovascular system disease that is located in the fibrous sac surrounding the heart. It is the same as something that has an intersection of being a disease and having a location in the pericardium. Moreover, pericardium disease is a type of cardiovascular system disease.
Peripheral artery disease is a type of artery disease that is defined by the buildup of plaque in the arteries that carry blood to your head, organs, and limbs.

Familial Encephalopathy with Neuroserpin Inclusion Bodies (FENIB) is a type of autosomal dominant, neurodegenerative disease that also shares characteristics common to diseases with a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. This condition is defined as a neurodegenerative disease characterized by intraneuronal inclusions of mutant neuroserpin, leading to progressive encephalopathy, dementia, and seizures. The disease has its material basis in a mutation in the SERPINI1 gene, which is inherited in an autosomal dominant pattern.
Pyrimidine metabolic disorder is a type of inherited metabolic disorder, defined as an inherited metabolic disorder involving dysfunction of pyrimidine metabolism.
Orotic aciduria is a type of pyrimidine metabolic disorder that is characterized by an excessive secretion of orotic acid in urine.

Charge syndrome is a type of syndrome that is characterized by a pattern of congenital anomalies, including choanal atresia and malformations of the heart, inner ear, and retina. It has an exact synonym, CHARGE association, and is exactly matched with MESH:D058747.

Generalized dystonia is a type of dystonia defined as a dystonia that affects most or all of the body. It has exact synonyms including familial dystonia and fragments of torsion dystonia. Additionally, generalized dystonia is relatedly synonymous with Dystonia 12.

Focal dystonia is a type of dystonia and is defined as a dystonia that is localized to a specific part of the body. It is the same as something that falls at the intersection of dystonia and something that, being at least a disease, has its location in some muscle organ.
Multifocal dystonia is a type of dystonia characterized by a condition that involves two or more unrelated body parts.
Segmental dystonia, a type of dystonia, is defined as a dystonia that affects two or more adjacent parts of the body.
Anismus is a type of focal dystonia and it is defined as a focal dystonia characterized by the failure of the pelvic floor muscles to relax during defecation.

Cervical dystonia, also known precisely as spasmodic torticollis, is a type of focal dystonia. It is defined as a focal dystonia characterized by the simultaneous contraction of the agonist and antagonist muscles that control the position of the head during dystonic movement. This condition causes the neck to involuntarily turn to the left, right, upwards, and/or downwards.

Focal hand dystonia is a type of focal dystonia and is also known as organic writer's cramp. It is characterized as a focal dystonia that affects a single muscle or small group of muscles in the hand, resulting from involuntary muscular contractions. Additionally, it is a type of disease that occurs in the hand.
An oculogyric crisis, which is a type of focal dystonia, is defined as a focal dystonia characterized by a prolonged involuntary upward deviation of the eyes.
Oromandibular dystonia is a type of focal dystonia, which is defined as a focal dystonia characterized by distortions of the mouth and tongue.

Spasmodic dystonia, which is a type of focal dystonia, is defined as a focal dystonia that involves the muscles controlling the vocal cords, leading to strained or breathy speech. Moreover, spasmodic dystonia is also exactly synonymous with laryngeal dystonia.
Craniofacial dystonia is a type of focal dystonia, which is defined as a focal dystonia characterized by affecting the muscles of the head, face, and neck.
Hemidystonia, which is a type of multifocal dystonia, is defined as a multifocal dystonia that involves the arm and leg on the same side of the body.
Sleep apnea is a type of sleep disorder defined as a sleep disorder characterized by repeated cessation and commencing of breathing that repeatedly disrupts sleep.

Obstructive sleep apnea is a type of sleep apnea with a specific definition: it is a sleep apnea characterized by repeated collapse and obstruction of the upper airway during sleep, leading to reduced airflow (hypopnea) or complete cessation of airflow (apnea), oxygen desaturation, and arousals from sleep. Additionally, obstructive sleep apnea is exactly synonymous with obstructive sleep apnea syndrome.

Periampullary adenoma is classified as a type of adenoma and specifically as a type of ampulla of Vater benign neoplasm. It falls under the category of neoplasms that originate from epithelial cells and glands. Furthermore, periampullary adenoma is defined as an ampulla of Vater neoplasm characterized by a glandular dysplastic lesion with pre-malignant potential.

Diabetic encephalopathy is a type of brain disease characterized by functional impairment of cognition, cerebral signal conduction, neurotransmission and synaptic plasticity, and underlying structural pathology associated with diabetes.
Glomerulosclerosis is a type of glomerulonephritis, which is defined as a glomerulonephritis that is characterized by the hardening of the glomerulus in the kidney.
Limb ischemia is a type of ischemia that is defined as an ischemia characterized by a low blood supply to tissues in the limb due to an interruption in the arterial blood supply.

Chronic venous insufficiency is a type of venous insufficiency that is defined as a venous insufficiency characterized by lower extremity swelling, hyperpigmentation, pruritus, and venous ulceration, which are caused by blood pooling in the veins.

Muckle Wells Syndrome (MWS), which is a type of syndrome, falls under the category of autosomal dominant diseases and is characterized by having a material basis in some form of autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by episodic skin rash, arthralgias, and fever associated with late-onset sensorineural deafness and renal amyloidosis, which is caused by a heterozygous mutation in the NLRP3 gene on chromosome 1q44. Additionally, Muckle Wells Syndrome is exactly synonymous with both MWS and neutrophilic urticaria.

Renal fibrosis is a type of kidney disease, defined as a kidney disease characterized by progressive detrimental connective tissue deposition in the kidney parenchyma, leading to deterioration of renal function.
Oppositional defiant disorder is a specific developmental disorder characterized by a pattern of angry mood, defiant behavior, and vindictiveness in children and adolescents.

Perrault syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease that has its material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by sensorineural hearing loss and ovarian failure.
Marshall Smith Syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by advanced bone age, failure to thrive, respiratory problems, dysmorphic facial features, and variable mental retardation.

Hemorrhagic cystitis is a type of cystitis and a type of condition that at least has the symptom of some hemorrhage. It is defined as a cystitis characterized by dysuria, hematuria, and hemorrhage, which is located in the lower urinary tract.

Colorectal adenoma is a type of intestinal benign neoplasm and a type of adenoma. It is also identified as a type of entity that intersects with something derived from epithelial cells and originates from a gland. Moreover, colorectal adenoma is defined as an intestinal benign neoplasm that has its material basis in epithelial tissue of glandular origin and is located in both the colon and the rectum.

Colorectal adenocarcinoma is a type of colorectal carcinoma and also a type of adenocarcinoma. It is defined as a colorectal carcinoma that derives from epithelial cells of glandular origin. Furthermore, it is categorized as something that derives from an intersection of something that is an epithelial cell and something that at least has its origin in a gland.

Pyometritis is a type of uterine disease and also a type of condition that has some inflammation as a symptom. It is defined as a uterine disease characterized by inflammation of the uterus and is associated with pus in the uterine cavity.

Arteritic anterior ischemic optic neuropathy is a type of anterior ischemic optic neuropathy. It is defined as an anterior ischemic optic neuropathy characterized by near-complete vision loss caused by damage to the medium-sized blood vessels supplying the optic nerves following temporal arteritis.

Non arteritic anterior ischemic optic neuropathy is a type of anterior ischemic optic neuropathy characterized by near-complete vision loss caused by acute ischemic damage to the optic nerve due to non-inflammatory small vessel disease. It is also known by its exact synonyms: non-arteritic anterior ischaemic optic neuropathy, nonarteritic anterior ischaemic optic neuropathy, and nonarteritic anterior ischemic optic neuropathy.

Tongue squamous cell carcinoma is a type of tongue cancer, and it is a specific form of head and neck squamous cell carcinoma that is located in the tongue. Furthermore, it is defined as a disease that has its location in at least some part of the tongue.

Oral squamous cell carcinoma is a type of squamous cell carcinoma, oral cavity cancer, and something that at least derives from squamous epithelial cells; it is also a type of disease that has its location in the mouth. This cancer has a material basis in squamous cells and is precisely synonymous with mouth squamous cell carcinoma.

Hepatocellular adenoma is a type of adenoma and a type of liver benign neoplasm. It is also a type of entity that intersects entities that at least derive from epithelial cells and those that at least originate from a gland. Hepatocellular adenoma is defined as a liver benign neoplasm that is located in liver cells and is composed of epithelial tissue, wherein tumor cells form glands or gland-like structures.

Spinocerebellar ataxia type 40 is a type of autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia, which is characterized by progressive gait abnormalities, dysarthria, tremor, and hyporeflexia. The condition has its material basis in a mutation in the CCDC88C gene.

Hypomyelinating leukoencephalopathy is a type of autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia and is defined as an autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia characterized by nystagmus, spasticity, and a distinct pattern of MRI abnormalities.

Grid2-related spinocerebellar ataxia is a type of autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia. It is defined as an autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia characterized by cognitive delay, abnormal eye movements, and hearing loss.

Episodic ataxia type 1 is a type of episodic ataxia that is defined by periodic ataxia and frequent myokymic discharges. This condition has a material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of a mutation in the potassium channel gene KCNA1.

Episodic ataxia type 2 is a type of episodic ataxia characterized by periodic ataxia and nystagmus. It has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance of a mutation in the calcium channel gene CACNA1A.

Episodic ataxia type 3 is a type of episodic ataxia that is defined as an episodic ataxia characterized by periodic ataxia, myokymia, vertigo, and tinnitus, with a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.
Episodic ataxia type 4 is a type of episodic ataxia, characterized by vertigo and diplopia.

Episodic ataxia type 5 is a type of episodic ataxia that is defined as an episodic ataxia characterized by dysarthria and vertigo, which develops in early childhood. It has a material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of a mutation in the CACNB4 gene.

Episodic ataxia type 6 is a type of episodic ataxia and is defined as an episodic ataxia that is characterized by nystagmus and dysarthria. It has a material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of a mutation in the SLC1A3 gene.

Episodic ataxia type 7 is a type of episodic ataxia and also falls under the category of conditions that typically present with at least some muscle weakness. It is defined as an episodic ataxia characterized by episodes of weakness and dysarthria, with a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance.

Episodic ataxia type 8 is a type of episodic ataxia and is characterized by weakness, dysarthria, and myokymia. This type of episodic ataxia is defined by its autosomal dominant inheritance of mutation in the UBR4 gene. Additionally, it is a type of condition that includes at least the symptom of some muscle weakness.

Cerebellar ataxia mental retardation and dysequlibrium syndrome is a type of syndrome that is classified as an autosomal recessive disease, which implies it has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by a congenital onset of nonprogressive cerebellar ataxia, disturbed equilibrium, and mental retardation, associated with cerebellar hypoplasia. The syndrome is also known by its exact synonyms: CAMRQ, Cerebellar Ataxia, Mental Retardation, and Dysequilibrium Syndrome 1 (CAMRQ1), Uner Tan syndrome, and VLDLR Cerebellar Hypoplasia.

Nonprogressive cerebellar ataxia with mental retardation is a type of autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia. It is defined as an autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia characterized by early onset of nonprogressive cerebellar ataxia, developmental delay, intellectual impairment, and cerebellar atrophy. This condition has a material basis in the autosomal dominant inheritance of a mutation in the CAMTA1 gene.

Autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 10 is a type of autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia, which is defined as an autosomal recessive cerebellar ataxia characterized by ataxia, dysarthria, nystagmus, and marked cerebellar atrophy. This condition has its material basis in a mutation in the ANO10 gene. Additionally, autosomal recessive spinocerebellar ataxia 10 is exactly synonymous with SCAR10.

Infective endocarditis is a subtype of endocarditis, which is characterized by inflammation of the endocardium caused by infectious agents. It falls under the category of bacterial infectious diseases and also fungal infectious diseases, indicating its material basis can be found in some bacteria and some fungi. Additionally, one of its symptoms includes inflammation.

Withdrawal disorder is a type of substance-related disorder and is also a type of condition that, at a minimum, involves alcohol as a disease driver. It is defined as a substance-related disorder that occurs upon the abrupt discontinuation/separation or a decrease in dosage of the intake of medications, recreational drugs, and alcohol.

C1 inhibitor deficiency is a type of complement deficiency characterized by a functional deficiency in the complement component C1 inhibitor, which leads to hereditary angioedema (HAE). This condition involves swelling due to leakage of fluid from blood vessels into connective tissue. Additionally, C1 inhibitor deficiency is exactly synonymous with Quincke edema.

An autoimmune disease of the central nervous system is defined as an autoimmune hypersensitivity disease situated in the central nervous system. This condition is equivalent to the intersection of an autoimmune disease and a disease that primarily affects the central nervous system. Furthermore, it is classified as a type of central nervous system disease, as well as a type of autoimmune disease of the nervous system.

An autoimmune disease of the endocrine system is defined as an autoimmune disease that results in the abnormal functioning of the immune system, leading to the production of antibodies or T cells against cells and/or tissues within the endocrine system. This condition is identified as being both a type of endocrine system disease and a type of autoimmune disease. Furthermore, it is equivalent to the intersection of an autoimmune disease and a disease that has its location in the endocrine system.
CD3zeta deficiency is a type of severe combined immunodeficiency that affects the development and function of T cells, characterized by its definition as a severe combined immunodeficiency.

Janus kinase 3 deficiency is a type of severe combined immunodeficiency and is characterized by severe cell-mediated and antibody-mediated immunodeficiency with recurrent bacterial, viral, and fungal infections. It develops from Janus kinase-3 deficiency and has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of mutation in the JAK3 gene of chromosome 19p13.11, which is responsible for normal differentiation and maturation of B and T immune cells.

MHC Class I deficiency is a type of severe combined immunodeficiency characterized by recurrent bacterial, viral, and fungal infections, especially of the lung, and sterile necrotizing granulomas of the skin. This condition develops from deficiency or decreased surface expression of MHC Class I and has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of mutation affecting MHC Class I production or expression, frequently involving TAP1 and TAP2 subunits, and is typically asymptomatic in infancy. It has exact synonyms including BLS, TYPE I, BLSI, HLA CLASS I DEFICIENCY, and bare lymphocyte syndrome type I.

Omenn syndrome is a type of severe combined immunodeficiency, which is also exactly synonymous with combined immunodeficiency with hypereosinophilia. It is characterized by having symptoms such as hepatosplenomegaly and diarrhea. The definition of Omenn syndrome includes being a severe combined immunodeficiency with a material basis in the RAG1 and RAG2 genes on chromosome 11p and the Artemis gene on chromosome 10p, and it is characterized by erythroderma, desquamation, alopecia, chronic diarrhea, failure to thrive, lymphadenopathy, and hepatosplenomegaly.

Recombinase activating gene 1 deficiency is a type of severe combined immunodeficiency, and it is defined as a severe combined immunodeficiency that results from a mutation on Chromosome 6 RAG1 gene. This mutation involves genetic rearrangement of both the T- and B-lymphocyte receptor genes.

Recombinase activating gene 2 deficiency is a type of severe combined immunodeficiency characterized by a severe combined immunodeficiency that results from a mutation on Chromosome 6 RAG2 gene. This involves the genetic rearrangement of both the T- and B-lymphocyte receptor genes.

X-linked severe combined immunodeficiency (SCID) is a type of X-linked recessive disease and a specific form of severe combined immunodeficiency. This condition also falls under the category of diseases that at least have a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a severe combined immunodeficiency that is a result of mutations in genes encoding common gamma chain proteins shared by the interleukin (IL-2, 4, 7, 9, 15, and 21) receptors. These mutations lead to a non-functional gamma chain, defective interleukin signaling, minimal or absent T- and NK cells, and non-functional B-cells. X-linked severe combined immunodeficiency is exactly synonymous with SCID-X1, XSCID, gamma chain deficiency, and thymic epithelial hypoplasia.

CD45 deficiency is a type of severe combined immunodeficiency, which is an autosomal recessive disease characterized by T and B lymphocyte dysfunction. This dysfunction is due to a large deletion at one allele and a point mutation at the other, with the point mutation resulting in the alteration of the intervening sequence 13 donor splice site. As a result of this condition, the population of T lymphocytes is diminished and unresponsive to mitogen stimulation, while the number of B lymphocytes and the level of serum immunoglobulin decrease with age.

Interleukin 7 receptor alpha deficiency is a type of severe combined immunodeficiency defined by a defective IL7R expression that causes T-B+NK+ SCID. This deficiency, also known exactly as IL-7R, results from the loss of IL-7R function which leads to the absence of an antiapoptotic signal, culminating in a loss of T-cell selection in the thymus.

CD3delta deficiency is a type of severe combined immunodeficiency that is characterized by the absence of T cells but normal numbers of B cells, indicating that CD3D is essential for T cell development. It also has the exact synonym CD3D.

CD3epsilon deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease, and it is also classified as a severe combined immunodeficiency. This condition is characterized by having a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, CD3epsilon deficiency is defined as a severe combined immunodeficiency that arises from autosomal recessive mutations in the gene responsible for encoding the precursors of the T-cell surface glycoprotein CD3epsilon chain. Patients suffering from CD3epsilon deficiency exhibit a significant defect in the expression of the T-cell receptor CD3-complex.

CD3gamma deficiency is characterized as a type of severe combined immunodeficiency and an autosomal recessive disease. This condition is specifically defined as a severe combined immunodeficiency that stems from autosomal recessive mutations in the gene responsible for coding T-cell surface glycoprotein CD3gamma chain precursors. Individuals with CD3gamma deficiency exhibit a significant defect in the expression of the T-cell receptor CD3-complex, leading to reduced T-cell numbers and function, while the impact on B cells varies.

Coronin 1a deficiency is a type of severe combined immunodeficiency, which is defined as an actin regulator mutation that results in SCID. This occurs through the inhibition of thymic egress of mature thymocytes into peripheral lymphoid organs.

Reticular dysgenesis is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a severe combined immunodeficiency, which is also the most severe form of SCID. It is characterized by its material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance and its phenotype of abnormal thymus morphology. Symptoms of reticular dysgenesis include lymphopenia. It is defined as a severe combined immunodeficiency with mutations in the gene encoding mitochondrial adenylate kinase 2, leading to congenital agranulocytosis, lymphopenia, and lymphoid and thymic hypoplasia with absent cellular and humoral immunity functions. Additionally, Reticular dysgenesis has the exact synonym "De Vaal disease" and a related synonym "aleukocytosis."

DNA ligase IV deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also categorized as a combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency. It has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and is characterized by a phenotype that includes growth delay. The condition is defined as a combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency that results from a mutation in the LIG4 gene. This gene encodes a DNA ligase, a protein essential for V(D)J recombination and DNA double-strand break (DSB) repair through the nonhomologous end joining (NHEJ) pathway. Patients with this deficiency present with immunodeficiency alongside developmental and growth delays. Additionally, DNA ligase IV deficiency is exactly synonymous with LIG4 Syndrome.

CD40 ligand deficiency is a type of X-linked recessive disease and a type of combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency, which at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency that is an X-linked immunodeficiency with hyperimmunoglobulin M (XHIM) affecting isotype switching. This condition is caused by the absence of CD40 ligand, which is normally expressed on activated CD4+ T cells, leading to individuals with this mutation being unable to switch from IgM to IgG, IgA, and IgE. CD40 ligand deficiency is also known by its exact synonyms HIGMX-1 and X-linked hyper-IgM syndrome.

Immunodeficiency with hyper IgM type 3 is classified as a type of autosomal recessive disease, hyper IgM syndrome, and also falls under conditions with a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a hyper IgM syndrome that occurs due to a mutation in the TNFRSF5 gene, leading to type 3 hyper-IgM immunodeficiency. This condition is characterized by the inability of B cells to undergo isotype switching, an inability to mount an antibody-specific immune response, and a lack of germinal center formation. It is precisely synonymous with CD40 deficiency, HIGM3, hyper-IgM syndrome due to CD40 deficiency, and type 3 hyper-IgM immunodeficiency. Furthermore, immunodeficiency with hyper IgM type 3 is accurately matched with several databases and identifiers, including GARD:10579, NCI:C176416, OMIM:606843, ORDO:101090, and UMLS_CUI:C1720957.

Lambda 5 deficiency is a type of monogenic disease, b cell deficiency, and something that has its basis in some gene. It is defined as a B cell deficiency that arises from mutations in the IGLL1 gene. These mutations can block B cell development at the transition between the pro-B cell and the pre-B cell stage.

Immunoglobulin alpha deficiency is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a type of B cell deficiency, which is something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a B cell deficiency that is an autosomal recessive disorder, having a material basis in mutation in the IgA (CD79 alpha) antigen receptor. Immunoglobulin alpha deficiency is exactly synonymous with IgA deficiency and gamma-A-globulin deficiency.

Immunoglobulin beta deficiency is a type of B cell deficiency, which is defined as a B cell deficiency characterized by mucosal infections and autoimmune diseases due to the lack of production of immunoglobulin A antibody. This deficiency has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance. Additionally, immunoglobulin beta deficiency is also related to the synonym "IgB deficiency."

Agammaglobulinemia 4 is a specific type of agammaglobulinemia and an autosomal recessive disease that fundamentally emerges from autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined by an agammaglobulinemia that results from a homozygous mutation in the BLNK gene located on chromosome 10q23.2. Furthermore, agammaglobulinemia 4 is precisely synonymous with B cell linker protein deficiency, B-cell linker protein deficiency, and BLNK deficiency.

Good Syndrome is a type of combined T cell and B cell immunodeficiency, which is defined as a condition where there is co-occurrence of deficient cell-mediated immunity and benign thymoma. It is also exactly synonymous with thymoma with hypogammaglobulinemia.

An autoimmune disease of the exocrine system is characterized by the abnormal functioning of the immune system, which leads to the production of antibodies or T cells against cells and/or tissues in the exocrine system. This condition falls under the broader category of autoimmune diseases and is defined by its occurrence when there's an intersection between diseases classified as autoimmune and those where the disease location is identified as the exocrine system. Essentially, an autoimmune disease of the exocrine system is a specific type of autoimmune disease that affects the exocrine system.

An autoimmune disease of the eyes, ears, nose, and throat is considered the same as an intersection of an autoimmune disease and a disease that has a location within the sensory system. Moreover, this type of autoimmune disease is classified as a type of sensory system disease and is also identified as a type of autoimmune disease within the nervous system. Additionally, it is defined as an autoimmune disease that is located in the eyes, ears, nose, and throat.

An autoimmune disease of the gastrointestinal tract is defined as an autoimmune disease characterized by the abnormal functioning of the immune system, which leads to the production of antibodies or T cells against cells and/or tissues in the gastrointestinal tract. This condition is also regarded as a type of autoimmune disease and is simultaneously considered a type of gastrointestinal system disease. Furthermore, it falls under the category of diseases that at least have the symptom of loss of appetite. Additionally, this disease is equivalent to the intersection of conditions that are autoimmune diseases and those diseases that are located in the digestive system, indicating its specific focus within the broader categories of both autoimmune and digestive system diseases.

An autoimmune disease of the musculoskeletal system is defined as an abnormal functioning of the immune system that causes it to produce antibodies or T cells against cells and/or tissues within the musculoskeletal system. This condition is the same as the intersection of an autoimmune disease and a disease that necessarily has a location within the musculoskeletal system. Furthermore, an autoimmune disease of the musculoskeletal system is classified as a type of musculoskeletal system disease and also as a type of autoimmune disease.

An autoimmune disease of the peripheral nervous system is defined as an autoimmune disease of the nervous system characterized by the abnormal functioning of the immune system, which leads to the production of antibodies or T cells against cells and/or tissues in the peripheral nervous system. This condition represents the intersection of autoimmune diseases and diseases located in the peripheral nervous system. Moreover, it is classified as a type of autoimmune disease of the nervous system and also as a type of peripheral nervous system disease.

Dropped Head Syndrome is a type of spinal disease, defined as a spinal disease characterized by severe kyphotic deformity of the cervicothoracic spine and by severe weakness of the cervical paraspinal muscles. This results in the passively correctable chin-on-chest deformity. The syndrome is defined by the weakness of neck extensor muscles against gravity, with or without weakness of neck flexor muscles. Dropped Head Syndrome is also exactly synonymous with Floppy Head Syndrome.

Intrinsic cardiomyopathy is a type of cardiomyopathy and also falls under the category of conditions that at least have the symptom of some muscle weakness. It is defined as a cardiomyopathy characterized by weakness in the muscle of the heart that is not due to an identifiable external cause.

Developmental disorder of mental health is a type of mental health disease. It is defined as a disease of mental health that occurs during a child's developmental period between birth and age 18, resulting in the retardation of the child's psychological or physical development.

A specific developmental disorder is a type of developmental disorder of mental health, which is defined as a developmental disorder that categorizes specific learning disabilities and developmental disorders affecting coordination.

Autoimmune disease of skin and connective tissue is identical to a condition that falls at the intersection of an autoimmune disease and a disease located in an area that encompasses both the skin and connective tissue zones. This disease is categorized as a type of autoimmune disease of the musculoskeletal system, a type of skin disease, and a type of connective tissue disease. Furthermore, it is defined as an autoimmune disease characterized by the abnormal functioning of the immune system, leading to the production of antibodies or T cells that target cells and/or tissues in the skin and connective tissue.

Pervasive developmental disorder is a type of developmental disorder of mental health, defined as a developmental disorder that refers to a group of five disorders characterized by impairments in socialization and communication, as well as restricted interests and repetitive behaviors. It also has exact synonyms, namely Pervasive Child Development Disorders and pervasive development disorder.

Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) is a type of pervasive developmental disorder and is defined as a spectrum of psychological conditions. This disorder is characterized by a variety of symptoms, including widespread abnormalities of social interactions and communication, severely restricted interests, and highly repetitive behavior. At least one of the symptoms of ASD includes some form of repetitive behavior.

Atypical autism is a type of autism spectrum disorder that involves some autistic symptoms occurring after the age of 3 with an absence of all the traits necessary for a diagnosis of autism. Additionally, atypical autism has an exact synonym: PDD.
Sexual health disorder is a type of mental health disease that is defined as a condition involving the impairment in normal sexual functioning.

Paraphilia disorder, a type of sexual health disorder, is defined as a sexual disorder characterized by recurrent, intense sexually arousing fantasies, sexual urges, or behaviors generally involving nonhuman objects.

Munchausen by proxy is a type of factitious disorder, which is defined as a factitious disorder that involves a caregiver's deliberate exaggeration, fabrication, and/or induction of physical, psychological, behavioral, and/or mental health problems in others.

Aphasia is a type of language disorder, which is defined as a language disorder that involves an acquired impairment of any language modality, such as producing or comprehending spoken or written language. Furthermore, Aphasia has an exact match to MESH:D001037.
A writing disorder is a type of learning disability characterized by impaired written language ability, which includes impairments in handwriting, spelling, organization of ideas, and composition.
Nosophobia is a type of specific phobia, defined as an irrational fear of contracting a disease.

An autoimmune disease of the urogenital tract is defined as an abnormal functioning of the immune system that causes your immune system to produce antibodies or T cells against cells and/or tissues in the urogenital tract. This condition is a type of autoimmune disease and is the same as the intersection of something that is an autoimmune disease and something that, at the very least, has its location in the genitourinary system.

An autoimmune disease of blood is identical to an entity that is both an autoimmune disease and a condition where at least one disease is located in the blood. Furthermore, an autoimmune disease of blood falls under the category of autoimmune diseases. It is defined as an autoimmune disease characterized by the abnormal functioning of the immune system, which leads to the production of antibodies or T cells against cells and/or tissues in the blood.

The autoimmune disease of the cardiovascular system is equivalent to an intersection of an autoimmune disease and any disease that is located in the cardiovascular system. It is classified both as a type of cardiovascular system disease and as a type of autoimmune disease. Additionally, the autoimmune disease of the cardiovascular system is defined as an abnormal functioning of the immune system that leads to the production of antibodies or T cells against cells and/or tissues in the cardiovascular system.

Autonomic peripheral neuropathy is a type of neuropathy defined as a neuropathy that affects the autonomic nervous system. It is characterized by urinary incontinence, gastrointestinal dysmotility, orthostatic hypotension, apneas, sweat disturbances, and impotence.

Popliteal pterygium syndrome, which is also known exactly as facio-genito-popliteal syndrome or popliteal web syndrome, is a type of autosomal dominant disease and syndrome. It is characterized by a condition that essentially has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. The syndrome is defined by abnormal development of the face, skin, and genitals, with clinical expressions including cleft lip, with or without cleft palate, contractures of the lower extremities, abnormal external genitalia, syndactyly of fingers and/or toes, and a pyramidal skin fold over the hallux nail. This condition is caused by mutations in the IRF6 gene located on chromosome 1.
Hypersensitivity reaction disease is a type of immune system disease that is defined as an immune system disease with a material basis in abnormal immune responses.

Gluten allergy is a type of food allergy and also a type of condition that entails at least having symptoms such as diarrhea. It is defined as a food allergy that develops from an immune reaction to eating gluten, a protein found in wheat, barley, rye, and triticale, and is characterized by stomach cramping, diarrhea, and gastrointestinal upset, distinguishing it from gluten intolerance. Additionally, gluten allergy has exact synonyms including "allergy to gluten" and "gluten allergic reaction."

Lymphoma is the same as something that is an intersection of cancer and something that at least has a material basis in some lymphocytes. It is a type of cancer that affects the lymphatic system, as well as a type of hematologic cancer. Additionally, lymphoma is a type of disease that has its location in some lymphoid tissue. Lymphoma is defined as a hematologic cancer that affects lymphocytes residing in the lymphatic system and in blood-forming organs. It also has the exact synonym "lymphoid cancer."
Non-Hodgkin lymphoma is a type of lymphoma, defined as any kind of lymphoma except Hodgkin's lymphoma.

Primary cutaneous T cell non-Hodgkin lymphoma is a type of peripheral T cell lymphoma and has a definition as a non-Hodgkin's lymphoma that has a material basis in a mutation of T cells. Furthermore, it has exact synonyms which are cutaneous T cell lymphoma and cutaneous T-cell lymphoma.

Familial juvenile hyperuricemic nephropathy is a type of kidney disease and something that begins during young adult onset. It is defined as a kidney disease characterized by hyperuricemia with renal uric acid under-excretion, gout, and chronic kidney disease.

Sideroblastic anemia 1 is a type of sideroblastic anemia and a specific form of X-linked recessive disease. It is characterized by microcytic hypochromic anemia and iron overload. This condition has a material basis in the X-linked inheritance of a mutation in the ALAS2 gene. This gene encodes aminolevulinic acid synthase, which catalyzes the first step in heme production. Sideroblastic anemia 1 is also known by several exact synonyms, including X-linked sideroblastic anemia, X-linked sideroblastic anaemia, XLSA, and sideroblastic anaemia 1.

Autosomal recessive pyridoxine refractory sideroblastic anemia 2 is a type of autosomal recessive disease, sideroblastic anemia, and something that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a sideroblastic anemia characterized by microcytic hypochromic anemia and iron overload, with a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of mutation in the SLC25A38 gene. Additionally, it has exact synonyms including autosomal recessive pyridoxine-refractory sideroblastic anaemia 2, pyridoxine-refractory autosomal recessive sideroblastic anaemia, and pyridoxine-refractory autosomal recessive sideroblastic anemia.

Pyridoxine responsive sideroblastic anemia, a type of sideroblastic anemia, is characterized by microcytic hypochromic anemia and iron overload. This condition has a material basis in X-linked inheritance.

Pearson syndrome is a type of mitochondrial metabolism disease, characterized by sideroblastic anemia and exocrine pancreas dysfunction. It is also exactly synonymous with Pearson Marrow-Pancreas Syndrome.

Nonbacterial thrombotic endocarditis is a type of endocarditis, which is also a type of something that at least has some endocarditis symptoms. It is defined as an endocarditis that results from the deposition of small sterile vegetations on valve leaflets. Moreover, nonbacterial thrombotic endocarditis has exact synonyms: marantic endocarditis and non-bacterial thrombotic endocarditis.

Pre-malignant neoplasm is a type of disease of cellular proliferation, defined as a disease of cellular proliferation that results in abnormal growths in the body. These growths do not invade or destroy surrounding tissue, but, given enough time, will transform into cancer.

Benign neoplasm is a type of disease of cellular proliferation and it is disjoint with cancer. It is defined as a disease of cellular proliferation that results in abnormal growths in the body which lack the ability to metastasize.

Lymphatic system cancer is defined as an immune system cancer that is located in the lymphatic system and is characterized by uncontrolled cellular proliferation of lymphoid tissue. This type of cancer is the same as the intersection of cancer and diseases located in some lymphoid tissue. Furthermore, lymphatic system cancer is a type of immune system cancer and also a type of lymphatic system disease.

Ductal carcinoma in situ is a type of breast carcinoma in situ characterized by its non-invasive nature, meaning it has not spread outside of the duct into the surrounding breast tissue. It has a material basis in abnormally proliferating cells and derives from epithelial cells.
Estrogen receptor positive breast cancer is a type of breast cancer characterized by the presence of estrogen receptors.
Estrogen receptor negative breast cancer is a type of breast cancer, which is defined as a breast cancer characterized by the absence of estrogen receptors.
Progesterone receptor positive breast cancer is a type of breast cancer characterized by the presence of progesterone receptors.
Progesterone receptor negative breast cancer is a type of breast cancer characterized by the absence of progesterone receptors.
Her2 receptor positive breast cancer is a type of breast cancer that is defined by the presence of Her2 receptors.
Her2 receptor negative breast cancer is a type of breast cancer characterized by the absence of Her2 receptors.
Triple receptor negative breast cancer is a type of breast cancer characterized by the absence of estrogen, progesterone, and Her2 receptors.

A breast benign neoplasm is defined as a thoracic benign neoplasm characterized by a lack of malignancy. It is equivalent to the intersection of a benign neoplasm and a disease that is located in the breast. Furthermore, a breast benign neoplasm is a type of thoracic benign neoplasm and also a type of breast disease.

Immune system cancer is the same as something that is an intersection of something that is cancer and something that has at least one disease located in the immune system. It is a type of organ system cancer as well as a type of immune system disease. Additionally, immune system cancer is defined as an organ system cancer located in the immune system, characterized by uncontrolled cellular proliferation in organs of the immune system.

The cell type benign neoplasm shares the same definition as something that intersects with a benign neoplasm and something that at least derives from some cell. Moreover, the cell type benign neoplasm is a type of benign neoplasm. Additionally, it is defined as a benign neoplasm that is classified by the type of cell or tissue from which it is derived.
An organ system benign neoplasm is a type of benign neoplasm that is classified by the organ system from which it arises.

A female reproductive organ benign neoplasm is defined as a reproductive organ benign neoplasm characterized by a lack of malignancy and is located in the female reproductive system. It is identified as the intersection of a benign neoplasm and a disease that has a location in the female reproductive system. Furthermore, it is classified as a type of reproductive organ benign neoplasm and also as a type of female reproductive system disease.

A male reproductive organ benign neoplasm, characterized by a lack of malignancy located in the male reproductive system, is equivalent to an intersection of a benign neoplasm and a disease at least having a location in the male reproductive system. This condition is a subtype of both reproductive organ benign neoplasm and male reproductive system disease.

Vestibular gland benign neoplasm is defined as a type of female reproductive organ benign neoplasm that is located in the vestibular gland. It is identical to an intersection involving a benign neoplasm and a disease that is located at least in some part in the vestibular gland.

Endocrine organ benign neoplasm is defined as an organ system benign neoplasm that is located in endocrine glands, which secrete a type of hormone directly into the bloodstream to regulate the body. This neoplasm is equivalent to the intersection of a benign neoplasm and a disease, where at least one disease is located in some endocrine gland. Furthermore, endocrine organ benign neoplasm is a subtype of organ system benign neoplasm.

A central nervous system benign neoplasm is the same as something that is both a benign neoplasm and a disease with at least one location in the central nervous system. This condition is a type of nervous system benign neoplasm and is also categorized as a type of central nervous system disease. It is defined as a nervous system benign neoplasm characterized by a lack of malignancy.

A cardiovascular organ benign neoplasm is identical to an entity that is both a benign neoplasm and a disease, which is located within the cardiovascular system. It is classified as a subtype of both organ system benign neoplasm and cardiovascular system disease. Additionally, a cardiovascular organ benign neoplasm is defined as an organ system benign neoplasm disease that is located in the blood, heart, blood vessels, or the lymphatic system.

An immune system organ benign neoplasm is equivalent to an entity that intersects with both a benign neoplasm and a disease that is located in some immune organ. It is a subtype of organ system benign neoplasm. Additionally, an immune system organ benign neoplasm is defined as an organ system benign neoplasm that is located in the immune system organs.

Bone benign neoplasm is the same as something that is an intersection of something that is a benign neoplasm and something that is at least a disease located in some bone element. Additionally, bone benign neoplasm is classified as a type of connective tissue benign neoplasm and also as a type of bone disease. Moreover, bone benign neoplasm is defined as a connective tissue benign neoplasm that is located in bone.

A uterine benign neoplasm is identified as an intersection of a benign neoplasm and a disease located in the uterus, indicating it is the same as something that is both a benign neoplasm and has a location in the uterus. It is a specific type of female reproductive organ benign neoplasm, as well as a type of uterine disease. Moreover, a uterine benign neoplasm is defined as a female reproductive organ benign neoplasm that is located in the uterus.

Sensory organ benign neoplasm is the same as something that is an intersection of benign neoplasm and something that is at least a disease located in some sensory system. It is a type of sensory system disease as well as a type of nervous system benign neoplasm. Moreover, sensory organ benign neoplasm is defined as a nervous system benign neoplasm that is located in a sensory organ.

A thoracic benign neoplasm is defined as an organ system benign neoplasm that is located in the thoracic cavity. It is the same as something that represents the intersection of a benign neoplasm and a disease, where the disease is located in some thoracic segment of the trunk. Furthermore, a thoracic benign neoplasm is classified as a type of organ system benign neoplasm as well as a type of thoracic disease.
Osteoblastoma is a type of bone benign neoplasm that is defined as a benign neoplasm of the bone characterized by clinical and histological similarity to osteoid osteomas.

A musculoskeletal system benign neoplasm is equivalent to an intersection of a benign neoplasm and a disease that is located in the musculoskeletal system. It is classified as a type of organ system benign neoplasm and also as a type of musculoskeletal system disease. Furthermore, a musculoskeletal system benign neoplasm is defined as an organ system benign neoplasm that is located in the muscular and skeletal organs.

Musculoskeletal system cancer is identical to an intersection of cancer and a disease that is located in the musculoskeletal system. Additionally, musculoskeletal system cancer is classified as a type of organ system cancer and also as a type of musculoskeletal system disease. It is defined as an organ system cancer that is located in the muscular and skeletal organs, characterized by uncontrolled cellular proliferation of these organs. Furthermore, musculoskeletal system cancer is exactly synonymous with skeletal system cancer.

Cartilage cancer is equivalent to an intersection of something that is both cancer and a disease, which is located in some cartilage tissue. It is a type of cartilage disease as well as a type of connective tissue cancer. Additionally, cartilage cancer is defined as a connective tissue tumor that can be either a benign chondroma or a malignant chondrosarcoma.

The central nervous system embryonal tumor is a type of cerebrum cancer and is also considered a type of disease located in the cerebrum. It is defined as a central nervous system cancer that occurs in children and young adults, developing from neural crest cells located in the cerebrum. This cancer has a material basis in cells that abnormally proliferate, deriving from neuroectoderm. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with CNS embryonal tumor, NEC/NOS, and also known as a central nervous system primitive neuroectodermal neoplasm.
Cerebellar medulloblastoma is a type of cerebellum cancer, which is defined as a cerebellum cancer that begins in the lower part of the brain on the floor of the skull.

Brain meningioma is the same as something that intersects with both meningioma and a disease located in the brain. It is identified as a type of brain cancer and also as a type of meningioma. The definition of brain meningioma is as follows: a brain cancer characterized by a tumor of the meninges, which develops from the membranes surrounding the brain and spinal cord. This condition has a material basis in abnormally proliferating cells that are derived from meningeal cells of embryonic ectoderm origin.
Brain glioma is a type of brain cancer that is defined as a brain cancer with a material basis in glial cells. It is also exactly synonymous with lower grade glioma.

Vulvar benign neoplasm is identical to an entity that is both a benign neoplasm and a disease, with the specific characteristic of being located in the mammalian vulva. It is classified as a type of female reproductive organ benign neoplasm and also falls under the category of vulvar diseases. Furthermore, it is defined as a female reproductive organ benign neoplasm that is located in the vulva.

A cervical benign neoplasm is identified as a condition that is both a benign neoplasm and a disease occurring at the location of the uterine cervix. It is classified as a type of uterine benign neoplasm as well as a type of cervix disease. Additionally, a cervical benign neoplasm is defined as a benign neoplasm of the female reproductive organ that is located in the cervix.

A fallopian tube benign neoplasm is defined as a female reproductive organ benign neoplasm located in the fallopian tube. It is the same as an intersection of something that is both a benign neoplasm and a disease, with at least one instance having its location in the fallopian tube. Additionally, it is categorized as a type of female reproductive organ benign neoplasm as well as a type of fallopian tube disease.

Ovarian benign neoplasm is identical to an entity that is both a benign neoplasm and a type of disease located in the ovary. It is classified as a type of female reproductive organ benign neoplasm as well as a type of ovarian disease. Additionally, ovarian benign neoplasm is defined as a female reproductive organ benign neoplasm located in the ovary.

Vaginal benign neoplasm is defined as a female reproductive organ benign neoplasm that is located in the vagina. It is identified as the same as the intersection of benign neoplasm and a disease that is located in the vagina. Furthermore, vaginal benign neoplasm is classified as a type of female reproductive organ benign neoplasm and also as a type of vaginal disease.

Nervous system benign neoplasm is the same as something that is an intersection of something that is a benign neoplasm and something that, at the least, has a disease located in some part of the nervous system. It is a type of organ system benign neoplasm and also a type of nervous system disease. Furthermore, nervous system benign neoplasm is defined as an organ system benign neoplasm that is located in the central nervous system or located in the peripheral nervous system.
