Sensory system cancer is equivalent to an intersection of cancer and a disease that is at least located in the sensory system. It is a type of sensory system disease and also a type of nervous system cancer. Sensory system cancer is defined as a nervous system cancer that is located in the sensory system.

A peritoneal benign neoplasm is identical to an entity that is both a benign neoplasm and a disease that is located in the peritoneum. Furthermore, a peritoneal benign neoplasm is categorized as a type of thoracic benign neoplasm. It is defined as a thoracic benign neoplasm that is found within the serous membrane lining the abdominal cavity or coelom.

Thoracic disease is the same as something that intersects with both a disease and something that has at least one disease located in some thoracic segment of the trunk. It is a type of disease of an anatomical entity. Furthermore, thoracic disease is defined as a disease of an anatomical entity that is located in the thoracic cavity.

Pharynx cancer, also known exactly as pharyngeal neoplasm or pharynx neoplasm, and relatedly referred to as pharyngeal cancer, is defined as a type of gastrointestinal system cancer located in the pharynx. It is identical to the intersection of something that is cancer and something that is at least a disease with its location in the pharynx.

Integumentary system benign neoplasm is the same as the intersection of benign neoplasm and a disease that has at least a location in some part of the integumentary system. It is a type of organ system benign neoplasm as well as a type of integumentary system disease. Furthermore, an integumentary system benign neoplasm is defined as an organ system benign neoplasm that is located in the organs of the integumentary system.

Integumentary system cancer is defined as an organ system cancer that is located in the skin, hair, and nails. It is the same as something that is both cancer and a disease, with at least one location being the integumental system. Additionally, integumentary system cancer is a type of organ system cancer and also a type of integumentary system disease.

Connective tissue benign neoplasm is identical to an entity that is an intersection of something that is a benign neoplasm and something that is at least a disease with a location in some connective tissue. It is a type of musculoskeletal system benign neoplasm and also a type of connective tissue disease. The definition of connective tissue benign neoplasm is a musculoskeletal system benign neoplasm that is located in connective tissue. Additionally, connective tissue benign neoplasm has several exact synonyms, including mesenchymal tissue neoplasm, neoplasm of soft tissue, neoplasm of soft tissues, soft tissue benign neoplasm, and tumor of the soft tissue.

Heavy chain disease is a type of hypersensitivity reaction type IV disease, which results from a proliferation of cells producing immunoglobulin heavy chains. Furthermore, it has an exact match with MESH:D006362.
Alpha chain disease is a type of heavy chain disease characterized by an overproduction of alpha antibodies (IgA). This condition is also known as Seligmann's disease.
Gamma heavy chain disease is a type of heavy chain disease characterized by an overproduction of gamma antibody (IgG). It is also known exactly as Franklin's disease.
Mu chain disease, which is a type of heavy chain disease, is defined as a condition that results from an overproduction of mu antibody (IgM).
Delta chain disease is a type of heavy chain disease and is defined as a heavy chain disease that results from an overproduction of delta antibody (IgD).
Akinetopsia is a type of agnosia, which is defined as an agnosia that results in a loss of motion perception.
Alexithymia, which is a type of agnosia, is defined as an agnosia characterized by a deficiency in understanding, processing, or describing emotions.

Amusia is a type of agnosia and is defined as an agnosia that involves the loss of the ability to recognize musical notes, rhythms, and intervals. Additionally, amusia is exactly synonymous with receptive amusia.
Anosognosia is a type of agnosia, which is defined as an agnosia that involves a loss of the ability to gain feedback about one's own condition or impairments.
Apperceptive agnosia is a type of agnosia defined as a loss of the ability to distinguish visual shapes.

Apraxia is a type of agnosia and is defined as an agnosia that is a loss of the ability to map out physical actions in order to repeat them in functional activities. Moreover, apraxia has an exact match with MESH:D001072.
Associative agnosia, a type of agnosia, is defined as an agnosia characterized by a loss of the ability to recognize visual scenes or classes of objects while retaining the ability to describe them.

Auditory agnosia is a type of agnosia defined as an agnosia that involves the loss of the ability to distinguish environmental and non-verbal auditory cues, including difficulty distinguishing speech from non-speech sounds, even though hearing is usually normal.
Autotopagnosia is a type of agnosia, defined as an agnosia that results in the loss of the ability to orient parts of the body.
Color agnosia, a specific type of agnosia, is defined as a loss of the ability to recognize a color, despite being able to perceive or distinguish it.
Cortical deafness is a type of agnosia, defined as an agnosia that involves the loss of the ability to perceive any auditory information, despite the hearing being intact.
Finger agnosia is a type of agnosia with the definition being an agnosia that is a loss of the ability to distinguish the fingers on the hand.
Form agnosia is a type of agnosia and is defined as an agnosia that involves the loss of the ability to perceive a whole object, resulting in only the perception of parts or details.
Integrative agnosia, a type of agnosia, is defined as a loss of the ability to integrate elements together into comprehensible perceptual wholes while recognizing elements of the whole.

Mirror agnosia is a type of agnosia, defined as an agnosia that involves a loss of the ability to acknowledge objects in the neglected field that are visible when a mirror reflects the object visible in the non-neglected field.
Pain agnosia is a type of agnosia and is defined as an agnosia that is a loss of the ability to perceive and process pain. It has the exact synonym analgesia.
Phonagnosia is a type of agnosia, which is defined as an agnosia that involves the loss of the ability to recognize familiar voices.

Semantic agnosia is a type of agnosia. It is defined as an agnosia that involves the loss of the ability to visually recognize an object while retaining the use of non-visual sensory systems such as feeling, tapping, smelling, rocking, or flicking the object to recognize it.

Simultanagnosia is a type of agnosia, defined as an agnosia that involves the loss of the ability to recognize a whole image or scene, while still retaining the ability to recognize objects or details in their visual field one at a time.

Social emotional agnosia, which is a type of agnosia, is defined as an agnosia that entails the loss of the ability to perceive facial expressions, body language, and intonation. This condition renders individuals unable to non-verbally perceive people's emotions, thereby limiting that aspect of social interaction. Additionally, social emotional agnosia is precisely synonymous with expressive agnosia.

Astereognosia is a type of agnosia and is defined as an agnosia that involves the loss of the ability to recognize objects by touch based on their texture, size, and weight. It is also exactly synonymous with somatosensory agnosia.
Tactile agnosia is a type of agnosia defined as the loss of the ability to recognize or identify objects by touch alone.
Time agnosia, a type of agnosia, is defined as a loss of the ability to comprehend the succession and duration of events.

Topographical agnosia is a type of visual agnosia and is defined as an agnosia that is a loss of the ability to rely on visual cues to guide them directionally due to the inability to recognize objects.
Verbal auditory agnosia is a type of agnosia defined as a loss of the ability to recognize spoken words as semantically meaningful.
Visual agnosia, a type of agnosia, is defined as the loss of the ability to visually recognize objects.
Visual verbal agnosia is a type of visual agnosia, defined as an agnosia that involves the loss of the ability to comprehend the meaning of written words.
Diffuse alopecia areata, a type of alopecia areata, is defined as an alopecia areata that involves diffuse loss of hair over the whole scalp.

Acquired metabolic disease is a type of disease of metabolism that is defined as a disease of metabolism with a material basis in enzyme deficiency or the accumulation of enzymes or toxins. These anomalies interfere with normal function due to factors like an endocrine organ disease, organ malfunction, inadequate intake, dietary deficiency, or malabsorption.

Organic acidemia is a type of amino acid metabolic disorder that disrupts normal amino acid metabolism, causing a buildup of branched-chain amino acids. It is also exactly synonymous with organic acid metabolism disorder and organic aciduria.

Childhood spinal muscular atrophy is a type of spinal muscular atrophy and also falls under the category of conditions that begin in childhood. It is defined as a spinal muscular atrophy associated with the survival of motor neuron protein in childhood, and it has its material basis in variation in the SMN gene. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with spinal muscular atrophies of childhood and survival motor neuron spinal muscular atrophy.

Kennedy's disease is a type of X-linked recessive disease and a form of spinal muscular atrophy, which inherently has a material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a spinal muscular dystrophy characterized by an X-linked recessive expansion of CAG triplet repeats (glutamine) in exon 1 of the AR gene, which encodes the androgen receptor. Kennedy's disease is also known by several exact synonyms, including Kennedy disease, SBMA, Spinobulbar Muscular Atrophy, X-Linked Bulbo-Spinal Atrophy, X-linked Spinal and Bulbar Muscular Atrophy, and spinal bulbar muscular atrophy.

Dentatorubral pallidoluysian atrophy (DRPLA), also known as Haw River Syndrome and Naito-Oyanagi disease, is a type of autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia. It is characterized by at least some degree of spinocerebellar tract degeneration. The condition is defined as an autosomal dominant cerebellar ataxia that has a material basis in the expansion of CAG triplet repeats (glutamine) encoding a polyglutamine tract in the atrophin-1 protein. Additionally, dentatorubral pallidoluysian atrophy has exact matches with several identifiers: MESH:D020191, NCI:C122653, and UMLS_CUI:C0751781.

Body dysmorphic disorder is a type of somatoform disorder defined as a somatoform disorder that involves an excessive concern about and preoccupation with a perceived defect in one's physical features (body image). It has exact synonyms, including body dysmorphia, dysmorphic syndrome, and dysmorphophobia.
Pain disorder, a type of somatoform disorder, is defined as a condition involving chronic pain in one or more areas, thought to be caused by psychological stress.
Kleine Levin Syndrome is a type of recurrent hypersomnia and is defined as a recurrent hypersomnia characterized by recurring periods of excessive amounts of sleep and altered behavior.

Bipolar II disorder is a type of bipolar disorder, defined as a bipolar disorder characterized by at least one hypomanic episode and at least one major depressive episode. With this disorder, depressive episodes are more frequent and more intense than manic episodes.

Seasonal affective disorder is a type of depressive disorder and is defined as a mental depression that involves the presentation of depressive symptoms only during a specific season of the year. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with winter depression.
Histidinemia is a type of histidine metabolism disease characterized by a deficiency of the enzyme histidase. It also has an exact synonym: histidinuria.

Benign familial infantile epilepsy is a type of infancy electroclinical syndrome that begins in the infantile onset period, specifically characterized by afebrile partial complex or generalized tonic-clonic seizures occurring between 3 and 12 months of age. It responds well to medication and leads to no neurologic sequelae. This condition is also precisely known by several synonyms including BFIC, BFIE, benign familial infantile convulsion, and benign familial infantile seizures.

Generalized Epilepsy with Febrile Seizures Plus (GEFS+) is a type of idiopathic generalized epilepsy. It is defined as an idiopathic generalized epilepsy that is characterized by febrile seizures, often accompanied by accessory afebrile generalized tonic-clonic seizures, with an onset in childhood. Additionally, it is exactly synonymous with GEFS+.

Juvenile absence epilepsy is a type of adolescence-adult electroclinical syndrome that begins during young adult onset, specifically starting between the ages of ten to 17 years. It is characterized by the occurrence of typical absence seizures.

Timothy syndrome is a type of autosomal dominant disease and syndrome, which has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance and a phenotype characterized by neurodevelopmental abnormalities. It is defined as a syndrome with cardiac, hand/foot, facial, and neurodevelopmental features, resulting from a heterozygous mutation in the CACNA1C gene on chromosome 12p13.33. This condition encompasses two forms: type 1 (classic) and type 2, a rare form caused by mutations in a transcript variant of the CACNA1C gene. Additionally, Timothy syndrome is related to and has a synonym known as long QT syndrome with syndactyly, and it has a broader match with UMLS_CUI:C1832916.

GABA aminotransferase deficiency is a type of gamma-amino butyric acid metabolism disorder that is characterized by a defect in the gene coding for gamma-aminobutyrate transaminase. This enzyme is responsible for the catabolism of gamma-aminobutyric acid (GABA), which is an important, mostly inhibitory neurotransmitter in the central nervous system, into succinic semialdehyde. Furthermore, GABA aminotransferase deficiency is exactly synonymous with both Gamma-amino butyric acid transaminase deficiency and gamma-aminobutyric acid transaminase deficiency.

Succinic semialdehyde dehydrogenase deficiency is a type of gamma-aminobutyric acid metabolism disorder characterized by a deficiency of succinic semialdehyde dehydrogenase, which results in elevated levels of gamma-hydroxybutyric acid. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with 4-hydroxybutyric aciduria, SSADH, and gamma-hydroxybutyric aciduria.
Gamma amino butyric acid metabolism disorder, a type of amino acid metabolic disorder, is characterized by an impairment of the GABA catabolic pathway.

Homocarnosinosis is a type of gamma-amino butyric acid metabolism disorder and a type of brain disease characterized by an excess of homocarnosine in the brain. It has a material basis in a deficiency of serum carnosinase in its ability to hydrolyze homocarnosine.

Familial hemiplegic migraine is a type of migraine with aura, defined as a migraine that is characterized by temporary numbness or weakness, often affecting one side of the body (hemiparesis). This condition also comes with additional aura features such as difficulty with speech, confusion, and drowsiness. Furthermore, it is associated with symptoms including confusion, drowsiness, muscle weakness, and hemiparesis.

Renpenning syndrome is a type of syndromic X-linked intellectual disability and a form of X-linked recessive disease. It is characterized by its material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance and presents symptoms such as short stature. The syndrome is defined as an intellectual disability characterized by small head size (microcephaly), long narrow face, short stature, small testes, and intellectual deficit, which follows X-linked inheritance and presents most often in males. Renpenning syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms including Golabi-Ito-Hall syndrome, Sutherland-Haan X-linked mental retardation syndrome, X-linked intellectual disability due to PQBP1 mutations, X-linked intellectual disability, Renpenning type, X-linked mental retardation Renpenning type, X-linked mental retardation with spastic diplegia, and syndromic X-linked mental retardation 8.
Colitis is a type of inflammatory bowel disease and is defined as an inflammatory bowel disease that involves inflammation located in the colon.
Ischemic colitis is a type of colitis that is defined as a colitis caused by inadequate blood supply to the colon.
Microscopic colitis, which is a type of colitis, is defined as a colitis that can only be diagnosed by the examination of colon tissue under a microscope.
Collagenous colitis is a type of microscopic colitis and is defined as a colitis characterized by a distinctive thickening of the subepithelial collagen table.
Lymphocytic colitis is a type of microscopic colitis and is defined as a colitis characterized by an accumulation of lymphocytes in the colonic epithelium and connective tissue (lamina propria).
Clostridium difficile colitis is a type of colitis that is characterized by an overgrowth of Clostridium difficile bacteria. It is also exactly synonymous with Pseudomembranous colitis.
Chemical colitis is a type of colitis defined as a colitis caused by the introduction of various chemicals.
Diversion colitis is a type of colitis, defined as a colitis caused by the diversion of the fecal stream due to complications of ileostomy or colostomy.

Jejunoileitis is a type of Crohn's disease and is characterized as an inflammatory bowel disease. This condition is distinguished by patchy areas of inflammation located in the jejunum. It exhibits symptoms such as abdominal pain, diarrhea, cramps, and the formation of fistulas. Additionally, jejunoileitis is associated with symptoms including abdominal cramps and pain.

Ileitis is a type of Crohn's disease, also known exactly as Crohn's ileitis. It is defined as an inflammatory bowel disease characterized by inflammation located in the ileum. This condition often presents symptoms such as diarrhea, abdominal pain, often in the right lower quadrant, and weight loss. Additionally, ileitis is associated with symptoms like weight loss, right lower quadrant abdominal pain, and diarrhea. Furthermore, this type of disease has its location in the ileum.

Ileocolitis is a type of Crohn's disease characterized as an inflammatory bowel disease. It is noted for inflammation that is located in both the colon and the ileum. This condition is associated with several symptoms, including diarrhea, weight loss, and abdominal pain specifically in the middle or lower right part. Additionally, ileocolitis entails symptoms such as inflammation, more weight loss, and right lower quadrant abdominal pain.

Gastroduodenal Crohn's disease, also known as upper GI Crohn's disease, is a specific form of Crohn's disease. It is defined as an inflammatory bowel disease characterized by inflammation located in the stomach and duodenum. This condition exhibits several symptoms, including inflammation, weight loss, loss of appetite, nausea, and vomiting. Additionally, it features duodenitis as part of its disease characteristics.

Crohn's colitis is a type of Crohn's disease, defined as an inflammatory bowel disease characterized by inflammation located only in the colon. It has symptoms including diarrhea, rectal bleeding, skin lesions, and the formation of ulcers, fistulas, and abscesses around the anus. Additionally, Crohn's colitis is associated with various symptoms, such as bleeding, inflammation, skin lesions, diarrhea, abscess, and anal abscess. It also features specific conditions like anal fistula and ulcers of the anus and rectum.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 1 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and also a type of autosomal recessive disease, indicating its complex inheritance patterns. It falls within the broader category of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis and is characterized by having a material basis in both autosomal dominant and autosomal recessive inheritance. This specific condition, also precisely known as ALS1 or amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 1, is defined as an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis that arises due to a mutation in the SOD1 gene on chromosome 21, representing the most common form of familial ALS.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 2 is a type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis. It is defined as an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis that has its material basis in a mutation in the alsin gene on chromosome 2. Additionally, amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 2 is exactly synonymous with ALS2, amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 2, and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 2, juvenile.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 3 is a type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis and has an exact synonym of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 3. It is defined as an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis that has a material basis in mutation in loci on chromosome 18. Furthermore, amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 3 is also relatedly synonymized as ALS3.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 4 is a type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, defined as an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis with juvenile onset that has a material basis in mutation in the SETX gene on chromosome 9. It is precisely known by several exact synonyms including ALS 4, amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 4, amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 4, juvenile, dHMN with upper motor neuron signs, distal hereditary motor neuropathy with pyramidal features, and distal hereditary motor neuropathy with upper motor neuron signs.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 5 is a type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis that is defined by an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis which has its material basis in mutation in the SPG11 gene on chromosome 15q21. Additionally, it has the exact synonyms ALS5 and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 5.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 6 is a type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, characterized by having its material basis in mutations in the FUS gene on chromosome 16. It is exactly synonymous with ALS6, amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 6, with or without frontotemporal dementia, and autosomal recessive amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 6.

Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis Type 7 is a type of Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis and has a definition as an Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis that has its material basis in a mutation in loci on chromosome 20. Furthermore, it has the exact synonyms ALS7 and Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis 7.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 9 is a type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis and has an exact synonym ALS9, as well as amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 9. It is defined as an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis that has its material basis in a mutation in the ANG gene on chromosome 14.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 10 is a type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, which is defined as an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis that has its material basis in mutation in the TARDBP gene on chromosome 1. It has several exact synonyms, including ALS10, TARDBP-related frontotemporal lobar degeneration with TDP43 inclusions, amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 10, and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 10, with or without frontotemporal dementia.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 11 is a specific type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis. It is defined by an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis that has its material basis in a mutation in the FIG4 gene located on chromosome 6. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with ALS11 and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 11.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 12 is a specific type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis. It is defined by an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis that has its material basis in a mutation in the OPTN gene located on chromosome 10. This condition is exactly synonymous with ALS12 and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 12.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 13 is a specific type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis. It is defined by a mutation with a material basis in the ATXN2 gene on chromosome 12, which contributes to susceptibility. This condition is exactly synonymous with both ALS13 and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 13.

Frontotemporal dementia and/or amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 6 is a type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, which is defined as an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis that has a material basis in mutation in the VCP gene on chromosome 9p13. This condition is also exactly synonymous with ALS14, amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 14, amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 14, and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, with or without frontotemporal dementia.

Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis Type 15 is a subtype of Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis. It is defined as an Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis that has its material basis in mutation in the UBQLN2 gene on chromosome X. Furthermore, Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis Type 15 is exactly synonymous with ALS15, Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis 15, and Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis 15, with or without Frontotemporal Dementia.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 16 is a type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, which has its material basis in mutation in the SIGMAR1 gene (SETX) on chromosome 9. It has exact synonyms including ALS16 and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 16. Furthermore, it is relatedly known as amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 16, juvenile.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 18 is a specific type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis. It is defined by an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis that has its material basis in a mutation in the PFN1 gene located on chromosome 17. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with ALS18 and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 18.

Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis Type 19 is a type of Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis, which is defined by having a material basis in mutation in the ERBB4 gene located on chromosome 2. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymous with ALS19 and Amyotrophic Lateral Sclerosis 19.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 20 is a type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, which is defined as an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis with juvenile onset that has its material basis in a mutation in the HNRNPA1 gene on chromosome 12. It is also exactly synonymous with ALS20 and amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 20.

Amyotrophic lateral sclerosis type 21 is a type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis, which has an exact synonym ALS21. This specific type is defined as an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis that has a material basis in mutation in the MATR3 gene on chromosome 5.

Frontotemporal dementia and/or amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 1 is a type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis. It is defined as an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis that has a material basis in mutation in the C9ORF72 gene on chromosome 9 and is characterized by the adult onset of either frontotemporal dementia and/or amyotrophic lateral sclerosis. This condition is exactly synonymous with ALSFTD, FTDALS1, FTDMND, amyotrophic lateral sclerosis and/or frontotemporal dementia, frontotemporal dementia and/or amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 1, and frontotemporal dementia and/or motor neuron disease.

Frontotemporal dementia and/or amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 2 is a specific type of amyotrophic lateral sclerosis. It is defined as an amyotrophic lateral sclerosis that has its material basis in a mutation in the CHCHD10 gene on chromosome 22, characterized by the adult onset of either frontotemporal dementia and/or amyotrophic lateral sclerosis. Furthermore, it is exactly synonymized as FTDALS2 and frontotemporal dementia and/or amyotrophic lateral sclerosis 2.

Balo concentric sclerosis is a type of multiple sclerosis that is characterized by concentric layers of demyelinated tissues, tumor-like lesions larger than two centimeters, and symptoms similar to those of a brain tumor. It is also known by exact synonyms such as Balo disease, Balo's concentric sclerosis, and Tumefactive multiple sclerosis.

Cogan syndrome is a type of eye disease characterized by nonsyphilitic interstitial keratitis located in the cornea and has symptoms such as fever and fatigue. It is also known by the exact synonyms Cogan's syndrome and diffuse interstitial keratitis.

Cogan Reese syndrome is a type of eye disease. It is defined as an eye disease characterized by variable iris atrophy, pigmented and pedunculated nodules located in the iris, and attachment of the iris to the cornea (peripheral anterior synechiae), which is also characterized by glaucoma.
Crest syndrome is a type of syndrome defined as a syndrome characterized by calcinosis, Raynaud's phenomenon, esophageal dysmotility, sclerodactyly, and telangiectasia.

Lymph node adenoid cystic carcinoma is a type of lymph node carcinoma, which is defined as a lymph node carcinoma characterized by a distinctive pattern where abnormal nests or cords of epithelial cells surround and/or infiltrate ducts or glandular structures of the lymph nodes. These structures are typically filled with a mucous-like material or contain abnormal fibrous membranes. Furthermore, lymph node adenoid cystic carcinoma has an exact synonym: lymph node adenoid cystic cancer.
Physical urticaria is a type of urticaria that is defined as an urticaria induced by external physical influences.
Maffucci syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by the presence of multiple enchondromas, which are benign growths of cartilage, associated with multiple hemangiomas.

Scheie syndrome is a type of mucopolysaccharidosis I and is characterized by corneal clouding, facial dysmorphism, and a normal lifespan. It has exact synonyms including mucopolysaccharidosis type 1S, mucopolysaccharidosis type IS, and mucopolysaccharidosis type V.

Agraphia is a type of writing disorder characterized by an acquired writing disorder causing a loss in the ability to communicate through writing, either due to some motor dysfunction or the inability to spell. Furthermore, agraphia has an exact match with MESH:D000381.

Atrial fibrillation is a type of heart conduction disease characterized by uncoordinated electrical activity in the heart's upper chambers (the atria), leading to a fast and irregular heartbeat. It manifests through various symptoms, including palpitations, weakness, fatigue, lightheadedness, dizziness, confusion, shortness of breath (dyspnea), chest pain, and arrhythmia. Additionally, atrial fibrillation is precisely synonymous with A-fib and AFib and has an exact match in the medical subject headings (MESH) database under the identifier D001281.

3mc syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease that primarily has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and exhibits symptoms like ptosis. It is defined as a syndrome characterized by blepharophimosis, blepharoptosis, highly arched eyebrows, hypertelorism, cleft lip and palate, postnatal growth deficiency, cognitive impairment, hearing loss and, in a smaller percentage of cases, craniosynostosis, radioulnar synostosis and genital and vesicorenal anomalies. This syndrome encompasses four disorders that were previously designated the Malpuech, Michels, Mingarelli, and Carnevale syndromes. Additionally, 3mc syndrome has exact synonyms, including craniofacial-ulnar-renal syndrome and oculopalatoskeletal syndrome.

Acrofrontofacionasal dysostosis is a type of dysostosis that is characterized by intellectual disability, short stature, hypertelorism, broad notched nasal tip, cleft lip palate, postaxial camptobrachypolysyndactyly, fibular hypoplasia, and anomalies of foot structure. It is also exactly synonymous with AFFN dysostosis and Richieri-Costa-Colletto syndrome.

Adams Oliver syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by defects of the scalp (aplasia cutis congenita), abnormalities of the fingers, toes, arms, and legs. It is also exactly synonymous with Adams Oliver syndrome.

An intracranial berry aneurysm, a type of intracranial aneurysm, is defined as an intracranial aneurysm with a characteristic rounded shape; it is the most common form of cerebral aneurysm. This aneurysm is also known by several exact synonyms, including familial aneurysmal subarachnoid hemorrhage, familial berry aneurysm, familial intracranial saccular aneurysm, and saccular cerebral aneurysm.

Baraitser Winter Syndrome is a type of syndrome that is characterized by distinctive facial features including hypertelorism, large eyelid openings, ptosis, high-arched eyebrows, a broad nasal bridge and tip of the nose, a long space between the nose and the upper lip, full cheeks, and a pointed chin. Moreover, this syndrome may also present structural abnormalities of the brain. It is notable for having at least one symptom, which is ptosis.

Basal ganglia calcification is a type of basal ganglia disease characterized by the presence of abnormal calcium deposits of unknown cause in the brain. This condition is also known exactly as Fahr disease. It has symptoms including dementia, psychosis, mood swings, and loss of acquired motor skills.

Bruck syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by a combination of multiple joint contractures and osteogenesis imperfecta. It is also exactly synonymous with osteogenesis imperfecta with congenital joint contractures.

Branchiootic syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by malformations of the outer, middle, and inner ear as well as branchial and renal malformations. This condition is associated with mutations of the EYA1, SIX1, and SIX5 genes. It is also known by its exact synonyms: BO syndrome, BOR, and branchiootic dysplasia.

Cardiofaciocutaneous syndrome is a type of monogenic disease, also recognized as a type of RASopathy, and it manifests with symptoms including heart failure. This syndrome's disease basis is rooted in genetics. It is defined as a RASopathy characterized by unusually sparse, brittle, curly hair, macrocephaly, a prominent forehead and bi-temporal narrowing, intellectual disability, failure to thrive, congenital heart defects, short stature, and skin abnormalities, with its material basis in mutations in the BRAF, MAP2K1, MAP2K2, and KRAS genes. Cardiofaciocutaneous syndrome is precisely synonymous with CFC syndrome and cardio-facial-cutaneous syndrome.

Carpenter syndrome is a type of acrocephalosyndactylia and is defined as an acrocephalosyndactylia characterized by craniosynostosis, acrocephaly, obesity, syndactyly, and polydactyly. It also has the exact synonym acrocephalopolysyndactyly type II.

Carnitine palmitoyltransferase II deficiency is a type of lipid metabolism disorder characterized by an enzymatic defect that prevents long-chain fatty acids from being transported into the mitochondria. It also has exact synonyms: CPT-II, infantile carnitine palmitoyltransferase II deficiency, late-onset carnitine palmitoyltransferase II deficiency, and lethal neonatal carnitine palmitoyltransferase II deficiency.

Xanthinuria is a type of autosomal recessive disease that falls under the category of purine-pyrimidine metabolic disorder. This condition is rooted in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. By definition, xanthinuria is characterized by a deficiency of xanthine oxidase, leading to the excretion of large amounts of xanthine in the urine and the formation of xanthine stones. It is also known by several exact synonyms, including classic xanthinuria, hereditary xanthinuria, xanthine dehydrogenase deficiency, and xanthine oxidase deficiency.

Warburg Micro syndrome is a type of syndrome and a specific autosomal recessive disease. It is defined by a group of symptoms including severe intellectual disability, microcephaly, congenital cataract, microcornea, microphthalmia, agenesis or hypoplasia of the corpus callosum, and hypogenitalism. This syndrome has several exact synonyms: WARBM, Warburg-Sjo-Fledelius syndrome, and micro syndrome. It is also described as having a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Van Maldergem Syndrome is a type of syndrome that is defined as a condition characterized by facial abnormalities, such as telecanthus, epicanthus, broad flattened nose, large inverted W-shaped mouth, and malformed ears, as well as malformed extremities including camptodactyly, clinodactyly, interdigital webbing, and joint hyperlaxity, along with mental retardation. It is an autosomal recessive disease, which means it has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Additionally, Van Maldergem Syndrome is exactly synonymous with cerebro-facio-articular syndrome.

Van der Woude syndrome is a type of syndrome characterized by the combination of lower lip pits, cleft lip with or without cleft palate, and cleft palate alone. It is also related to and synonymously known as lip-pit syndrome.

UV sensitive syndrome is a skin disease characterized by autosomal recessive inheritance, indicating it is a type of autosomal recessive disease that at least has a material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. Furthermore, it is defined as a skin disease characterized by photosensitivity and liver spots (solar lentigines).

3 M syndrome is a type of syndrome and an autosomal recessive disease that has its material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is characterized by dwarfism, facial dysmorphia, and skeletal abnormalities. This syndrome is also known by several exact synonyms, including Le Merrer syndrome, Miller-McKusick-Malvaux syndrome, Yakut short stature syndrome, dolichospondylic dysplasia, gloomy face syndrome, and three M syndrome.

Synpolydactyly, a type of syndactyly, is characterized by an increased number of digits; this condition is often a result of a mutation in the HOXD13 gene. It is also exactly synonymous with syndactyly type 2.

Stuttering is a type of articulation disorder, which is characterized by involuntary sound repetition and disruption or blocking of speech. Additionally, stuttering is exactly synonymous with familial persistent stuttering and stammering.

Specific language impairment is a type of language disorder characterized by difficulty in language acquisition despite otherwise normal development and in the absence of any obvious explanatory factors.

Mast syndrome is a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia and is defined as a hereditary spastic paraplegia associated with dementia. It is exactly synonymous with SPG21, autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia 21, autosomal recessive spastic paraplegia type 21, and hereditary spastic paraplegia 21.

Masa syndrome is a type of X-linked recessive disease and also a type of hereditary spastic paraplegia, which at least has a material basis in some X-linked recessive inheritance. It is defined as a hereditary spastic paraplegia characterized by hydrocephalus, spasticity of the lower limbs, adducted thumbs, aphasia, seizures, agenesis of the corpus callosum, and intellectual disability in the mild to moderate range. Masa syndrome is known by several exact synonyms, including CRASH syndrome, Gareis-Mason syndrome, L1 syndrome, SPG1, X-linked complicated hereditary spastic paraplegia type 1, X-linked corpus callosum agenesis, X-linked spastic paraplegia 1, and hereditary spastic paraplegia 1.
Smith-McCort dysplasia is a type of Dyggve-Melchior-Clausen disease that is characterized by short limbs and a short trunk with a barrel-shaped chest.

Simpson Golabi Behmel Syndrome Type 1 is a type of syndrome and is specifically categorized as an X-linked recessive disease. This syndrome is defined by its material basis in X-linked recessive inheritance. It is characterized by pre- and postnatal overgrowth, along with craniofacial, skeletal, cardiac, and renal abnormalities. These characteristics have their material basis in a mutation in the gene encoding glypican-3 (GPC3) on chromosome Xq26. 

Furthermore, Simpson Golabi Behmel Syndrome Type 1 is also known by several exact synonyms, including DGSX Golabi-Rosen Syndrome, Golabi-Rosen Syndrome, SGB Syndrome, Sara Angers Syndrome, Simpson Dysmorphia Syndrome, X-linked Dysplasia Gigantism Syndrome, and Bulldog Syndrome.

Scoliosis is a type of spinal disease and a type of bone structure disease. It is characterized by an abnormal curvature of the vertebral column, indicating that the disease primarily affects the vertebral column. Scoliosis is defined as a bone structure disease characterized by an appreciable lateral deviation in the normally straight vertical line of the spine. Additionally, scoliosis has an exact match with MESH:D012600.
Idiopathic scoliosis is a type of scoliosis characterized by having no known cause.

Sclerosteosis is a type of hyperostosis, defined by excessive bone formation most prominently observed in the skull, mandible, clavicle, ribs, and diaphyses of long bones. This bone formation continues throughout life.

Sclerocornea is a type of corneal disease that is defined as a corneal disease in which the cornea blends with the sclera, resulting in clouding of the cornea. It is exactly synonymous with isolated congenital sclerocornea.

Scapuloperoneal myopathy is a type of muscular dystrophy characterized by a specific pattern of weakness that begins at the lower legs and affects the shoulder region earlier and more severely than the distal arm.

Robinow syndrome is a type of autosomal genetic disease and a type of syndrome that has its material basis in autosomal inheritance. It is characterized by mild to moderate short stature due to growth delays after birth, distinctive craniofacial abnormalities, skeletal malformations, and genital abnormalities. Robinow syndrome is exactly synonymous with Robinow dwarfism, acral dysostosis with facial and genital abnormalities, and fetal face syndrome.

Rippling muscle disease 2 is a type of autosomal dominant disease and a type of muscle tissue disease, which is characterized by something that has a material basis in autosomal dominant inheritance. It is defined as a muscle tissue disease characterized by mechanically triggered contractions of skeletal muscle, which has its material basis in mutations in the caveolin-3 gene (CAV3) on chromosome 3p25. Additionally, rippling muscle disease 2 has the exact synonym autosomal dominant limb-girdle muscular dystrophy type 1C.

Dowling Degos Disease is a type of pigmentation disease and is characterized by a pigmentation disease with a distinct reticulate pattern of abnormally dark skin coloring, especially noticeable in the body's folds and creases. It is also known by its exact synonyms, Dark Dot Disease and Reticular Pigment Anomaly of Flexures.

Dyschromatosis symmetrica hereditaria is a type of pigmentation disease characterized by progressively pigmented and depigmented macules, often mixed in a reticulate pattern, concentrated on the dorsal extremities. It is also known exactly as reticulate acropigmentation of Dohi.

Reticulate acropigmentation of Kitamura is a type of pigmentation disease characterized by lesions that initially arise as letiginous, hyperpigmented macules in a reticular pattern on the dorsal aspect of the hands and feet. Over time, these lesions may spread proximally and may darken; palmoplantar pitting and dermatoglyphic disruption may also be present. It has an exact synonym, RAPK.

Renal hepatic pancreatic dysplasia is a type of physical disorder characterized by pancreatic fibrosis, renal dysplasia, and hepatic dysgenesis; it is usually fatal soon after birth. It is also known exactly as Ivemark's syndrome.
Ptosis is a type of eye disease characterized by the drooping or falling of the upper or lower eyelid. It is also known by its exact synonyms, blepharoptosis and drooping eyelid.

Congenital ptosis is a type of ptosis and also a type of physical disorder. It is defined as a ptosis characterized by eyelid drop present at birth. This condition is recognized as a type of issue that has its basis in some abnormality of prenatal development or birth.

Gallbladder disease is the same as a disease that intersects with a disease having at least one location in the gallbladder. It is a type of gastrointestinal system disease. Furthermore, gallbladder disease is defined as a gastrointestinal system disease that is located in the gallbladder.
Porencephaly is a type of brain disease characterized by encephalomalacia and cystic brain lesions.
Pontocerebellar hypoplasia is a type of neurodegenerative disease, which is characterized by the underdevelopment of the pons and cerebellum. It is also exactly known as PCH.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 1a is a type of pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 1 and an autosomal recessive disease, which means it is a subset of conditions that have a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a pontocerebellar hypoplasia characterized by central and peripheral motor dysfunction, hypotonia, spasticity, and failure to thrive, with its material basis being in homozygous or compound heterozygous mutation in the VRK1 gene.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 1b is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which falls under the broader category of pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 1, and is a condition that at least has its material basis in some autosomal recessive inheritance. It is defined as a severe pontocerebellar hypoplasia characterized by hypotonia, progressive microcephaly, and developmental delay, with its material basis in the autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the EXOSC3 gene.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 2a is a specific type of autosomal recessive disease and also falls under the broader category of pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 2. This condition is a form of pontocerebellar hypoplasia that is notably severe and characterized by progressive microcephaly, chorea, epilepsy, and hyperreflexia, which results from an autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the TSEN54 gene. This implies that pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 2a is essentially a manifestation of a disease that fundamentally has its material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 2b is a type of autosomal recessive disease and also a subtype of pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 2. It is characterized by being a condition that, at the very least, has a material basis in some form of autosomal recessive inheritance. Specifically, pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 2b is defined as a severe form of pontocerebellar hypoplasia characterized by progressive microcephaly, clonus, dysphagia, and failure to thrive. This condition has its material basis in the autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the TSEN2 gene.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 2c is a type of autosomal recessive disease, which is also a subtype of pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 2. It is characterized as a severe condition marked by progressive microcephaly, extrapyramidal dyskinesia, seizures, and failure to thrive. This disease fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance, particularly through mutations in the TSEN34 gene.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 2d is a specific form of pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 2 and is categorized as an autosomal recessive disease. It is defined as a type of pontocerebellar hypoplasia characterized by progressive microcephaly, profound intellectual disability, spasticity, and seizures. This condition fundamentally arises from autosomal recessive inheritance, specifically due to mutations in the SEPSECS gene.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 2e is a type of autosomal recessive disease and a subtype of pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 2. It is characterized by progressive microcephaly, profound intellectual disability, spasticity, and seizure, due to the autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the VPS53 gene. This condition exemplifies something that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 3 is a specific type of pontocerebellar hypoplasia, characterized by progressive microcephaly, hypotonia, dysmorphic features, profound intellectual disability, and seizures. This condition has a material basis in the autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the PCLO gene.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 4 is a type of pontocerebellar hypoplasia characterized by progressive microcephaly, hypertonia, myoclonus, seizure, and early lethality. It has its material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the TSEN54 gene.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 5 is a subtype of pontocerebellar hypoplasia. It is defined as a pontocerebellar hypoplasia characterized by severe olivopontocerebellar hypoplasia and degeneration, which leads to early lethality. This condition has a material basis in the autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the TSEN54 gene.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 6 is a subtype of pontocerebellar hypoplasia. It is defined as a pontocerebellar hypoplasia that features olivopontocerebellar hypoplasia and developmental delay. This condition arises due to autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the RARS2 gene.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 7 is a specific type of pontocerebellar hypoplasia that is defined by its characteristics of delayed psychomotor development, hypotonia, gonadal abnormalities, and respiratory failure. This condition is caused by an autosomal recessive mutation in the TOE1 gene.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 8 is a specific type of pontocerebellar hypoplasia, characterized by delayed psychomotor development, chorea, hypotonia, spasticity, and visual defects. This condition arises from an autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the CHMP1A gene.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 9 is a specific form of pontocerebellar hypoplasia. It is defined as a type of pontocerebellar hypoplasia that manifests through progressive microcephaly, spasticity, seizures, and brain atrophy. This condition arises from the autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the AMPD2 gene.

Pontocerebellar hypoplasia type 10 is a type of pontocerebellar hypoplasia and is defined by severe developmental delays, progressive microcephaly, spasticity, and seizures. It has a material basis in the autosomal recessive inheritance of a mutation in the CLP1 gene.
Primary pigmented nodular adrenocortical disease is a type of adrenal cortex disease that is defined by small to normal sized adrenal glands containing multiple small cortical pigmented nodules.

Photosensitive epilepsy is a type of epilepsy characterized by seizures triggered by visual stimuli that form patterns in space or time, such as flashing lights. It is also exactly synonymous with photogenic epilepsy and photoparoxysmal response.

Persistent hyperplastic primary vitreous is a type of vitreous disease. It is defined as a developmental vitreous disease characterized by leukocoria, strabismus, and vision loss, caused by the failure of the primary vitreous and hyaloid vasculature to regress during embryological development.

Peeling skin syndrome is a type of autosomal recessive and skin disease that at least has a material basis in autosomal recessive inheritance and has symptoms including skin peeling. It is characterized by the painless, continuous peeling of the top layer of skin. Peeling skin syndrome is also known by exact synonyms such as PSS, deciduous skin, familial continuous skin peeling syndrome, keratosis exfoliativa congenita, and peeling skin disease. Furthermore, peeling skin syndrome matches broader medical classification ICD10CM:Q80.8, and it has exact matches with several medical databases and classification systems including GARD:7347, OMIM:PS270300, ORDO:817, SNOMEDCT_US_2023_03_01:724838009, and UMLS_CUI:C1849193.

Paroxysmal nocturnal hemoglobinuria is a type of hemoglobinuria with a definition that specifies it as an acquired hemolytic anemia. It is characterized by symptoms such as abdominal pain, hematuria, esophageal dysmotility, and thrombosis. The condition has a material basis in a defect in the cell membrane glycosyl phosphatidylinositols that protect red blood cells from the innate complement immune system.

Parietal foramina is a type of neural tube defect and is defined as an inherited neural tube defect characterized by enlarged openings in the parietal bones of the skull. This condition has its material basis in mutations in the ALX4 gene or MSX2 gene. It is also exactly synonymous with Caitlin marks, enlarged parietal foramina, and hereditary cranium bifidum.

Combined oxidative phosphorylation deficiency is a type of mitochondrial metabolism disease characterized by growth retardation, microcephaly, hypertonia, encephalopathy, cardiomyopathy, and liver dysfunction.
Cornea plana is a type of corneal disease characterized by a flat cornea where the radius of curvature is less than 43 D. It is also exactly synonymous with the term "flat cornea."
